"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789981","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>The government keeps all taxes under review at fiscal events, and we will consider this issue carefully as part of the Autumn Budget process.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789981/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T11:18:56.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789981/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789981/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will reform the duty regime for super strength alcohol to incentivise a reduction in the strength of those products.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","113325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789982","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>HMRC does not have power to acquire journalistic material held overseas and, therefore, is unable to obtain the information held by the ICIJ ‎known as the Paradise Papers. However, HMRC has requested access to the material that has been provided by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists to the BBC and <em>The Guardian</em>. HMRC has also encouraged these organisations to pass on any information that points to wrongdoing and are prepared to look at every allegation in full.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789982/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T14:25:03.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789982/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789982/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Appleby: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has taken legal steps to obtain information held by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists relating to the Paradise papers.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789983","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>HM Revenue and Customs is not itself a prosecuting authority. All prosecutions have to be authorised by the relevant independent prosecuting authority, which for England and Wales would be the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS); for Scotland, the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service (COPFS); and for Northern Ireland, the Public Prosecution Service for Northern Ireland (PPSNI).</p><p> </p><p>The custodial sentences handed down in a particular financial year may be in respect of charging decisions made in previous years, due to the length of time individuals can take to proceed through the judicial system from charging decision to outcome. They therefore do not correlate directly to the number of charging decisions in that financial year.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Positive Charging Decisions</p></td><td><p>Number of Custodial Sentences Handed Down</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>501</p></td><td><p>241</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>739</p></td><td><p>227</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>880</p></td><td><p>241</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1254</p></td><td><p>247</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>1067</p></td><td><p>272</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>1067</p></td><td><p>292</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789983/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T14:37:39.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789983/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789983/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people were charged with tax evasion in each year from 2010 to date; and how many of those people served a custodial sentence as a result of that tax evasion.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789984","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) wrote to around 800,000 families affected by the introduction of the High Income Child Benefit Charge (HICBC) in the autumn of 2012, covering the majority of those affected. HMRC also wrote to two million PAYE-only higher rate taxpayers in the summer of 2013 and included a reminder about the need to register for Self Assessment to declare Child Benefit payments. This ensured that as many affected families as possible were aware of what they needed to do in relation to the charge.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789984/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T10:07:13.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789984/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789984/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Child Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people who were not contacted directly about the introduction of the high income child benefit charge in 2012.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","113184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789985","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will consider offering redress if a customer has incurred a financial loss. As at 15 November 2017, HMRC had paid a total of £18,035 in payments for costs, actual financial loss or reimbursement due to actions taken by Concentrix during the course of its contract.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will consider offering redress if a customer has incurred a financial loss. As at 15 November 2017, HMRC had made 1,271 payments for costs, actual financial loss or reimbursement due to action taken by Concentrix during the course of its contract.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789985/answer",,,,,"113212","2017-11-20T13:48:19.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789985/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789985/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much compensation HM Revenue and Customs paid to tax credit claimants who incurred a financial loss due to actions taken by Concentrix during the course of its contract in relation to error and fraud in the tax credits system.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","113211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789986","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will consider offering redress if a customer has incurred a financial loss. As at 15 November 2017, HMRC had paid a total of £18,035 in payments for costs, actual financial loss or reimbursement due to actions taken by Concentrix during the course of its contract.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will consider offering redress if a customer has incurred a financial loss. As at 15 November 2017, HMRC had made 1,271 payments for costs, actual financial loss or reimbursement due to action taken by Concentrix during the course of its contract.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789986/answer",,,,,"113211","2017-11-20T13:48:19.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789986/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789986/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many claimants have received a compensation payment from HM Revenue and Customs as a result of an actual financial loss caused by the actions of Concentrix during its contract in relation to the tax credits system.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","113212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789987","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789987/answer","PQ113231.pdf","PQ113231.pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response",,"2017-12-01T14:22:40.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789987/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789987/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-15","Pay: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside and (c) the North East earn below the UK average weekly earnings for full-time employees.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","113231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789988","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-24","<p>Between 2014-16, the UK received around €3.3bn or 11.9% of total Horizon 2020 funding. Details of individual years are shown in the table below, which can be found at the following link: <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/budget/figures/interactive/index_en.cfm" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/budget/figures/interactive/index_en.cfm</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>Total 2014-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK Horizon 2020 funding, €m nominal</p></td><td><p>748</p></td><td><p>1210</p></td><td><p>1318</p></td><td><p>3276</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK Horizon 2020 funding as a share of total Horizon 2020 expenditure</p></td><td><p>10.1%</p></td><td><p>12.6%</p></td><td><p>12.4%</p></td><td><p>11.9%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789988/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:58:22.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789988/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789988/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Horizon 2020","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the UK's total receipts from the EU Horizon 2020 programme were in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","113161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789989","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>The government keeps all taxes under review. Any changes to wine duty rates would need to take account of a wide range of factors, including the Exchequer impact, the impact on businesses, public health and the distributional impact of reform.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789989/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T11:28:59.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789989/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789989/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Sparkling Wines: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of regularising the rate of duty between sparkling wine produced in the UK and such wine produced in France.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","113167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789990","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>Tax Impact and Information Notes (TIINS) are published alongside new tax measures and represent the estimated impact of a measure at that time. TIINs published for previous measures are not retrospectively edited.</p><p> </p><p>The government keeps all taxes under review at fiscal events, and we will consider this issue carefully as part of the Autumn Budget process.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789990/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T10:57:10.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789990/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789990/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to update the Exchequer Impact data on the Tax Impact Information Note relating to alcohol duty rate changes; and if he will halt planned increases in wine duty.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","113168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789991","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) was formed in 2005. To go back further than 2005, given the changes in departmental structure and amendments to the definition and calculation of compliance yield, would mean the figures would not be comparable.</p><p> </p><p>Compliance yield includes cash expected and an estimate of the amount of revenue HMRC prevented from being lost, together with the impact of legislative changes, process improvements and current compliance activity on future customer behaviour.</p><p> </p><p>With reference to the below table of annually reported compliance yield, HMRC generated £52 billion of compliance yield by tackling avoidance, evasion and non-compliance from 2005-06 to 2009‑10. From the start of 2010‑11 through to quarter 1 2017-18, HMRC has generated over £160 billion in compliance yield.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Compliance yield (£bn)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>7.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>8.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>11.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>12.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>12.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>13.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>18.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>20.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>23.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>26.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>26.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>28.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Details on how compliance yield is calculated, and its various components, can be found in HMRC’s Annual Reports and quarterly performance publications.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789991/answer",,,,,"113407","2017-11-24T09:54:35.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789991/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789991/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Tax Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much of £160 billion of extra revenue that HM Revenue and Customs estimates has been secured as a result of tax compliance activities has been collected.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","113405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789992","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) was formed in 2005. To go back further than 2005, given the changes in departmental structure and amendments to the definition and calculation of compliance yield, would mean the figures would not be comparable.</p><p> </p><p>Compliance yield includes cash expected and an estimate of the amount of revenue HMRC prevented from being lost, together with the impact of legislative changes, process improvements and current compliance activity on future customer behaviour.</p><p> </p><p>With reference to the below table of annually reported compliance yield, HMRC generated £52 billion of compliance yield by tackling avoidance, evasion and non-compliance from 2005-06 to 2009‑10. From the start of 2010‑11 through to quarter 1 2017-18, HMRC has generated over £160 billion in compliance yield.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Compliance yield (£bn)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>7.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>8.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>11.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>12.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>12.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>13.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>18.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>20.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>23.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>26.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>26.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>28.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Details on how compliance yield is calculated, and its various components, can be found in HMRC’s Annual Reports and quarterly performance publications.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789992/answer",,,,,"113405","2017-11-24T09:54:35.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789992/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789992/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Tax Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much extra revenue HM Revenue and Customs secured during the years 1997 to 2010 as a result of tax compliance activities.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","113407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789993","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-24","<p>I refer the Right Honourable Member to the Answer which I gave to PQ 112100 on 16 November 2017.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789993/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T09:51:30.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789993/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789993/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many times HM Revenue and Customs has requested beneficial ownership information from each register of beneficial ownership from the UK's Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies since 1 July 2017.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","113408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789994","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>The UK's VAT registration threshold is currently set at £85,000. Businesses must register for VAT when their turnover is above £85,000. Businesses below the threshold are eligible to register voluntarily if making taxable supplies.</p><p> </p><p>To assess the impact of VAT on small and medium enterprises HM Revenue and Customs commissioned Ipsos MORI to conduct research into their behaviours and experiences around VAT registration. The report was published on 16 November 2017.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789994/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T14:41:39.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789994/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789994/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-15","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of changes to eligibility for VAT registration on (a) guest houses and bed and breakfast outlets and (b) other small and medium-sized enterprises.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","113430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789995","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Department does not employ any full or part time members of staff with the sole responsibility for social media.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789995/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T16:28:55.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789995/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789995/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-15","Department for Communities and Local Government: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people in his Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789996","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-23","<p>Integration funding is used to support work which brings communities together and promotes tolerance. Under section 70 (1) of the Charities Act 2006, a relevant Minister may give financial assistance to any charitable, benevolent or philanthropic institution in respect of any of the institution's activities which directly or indirectly benefit the whole or any part of England. Proposals from any organisations, including those with a significant faith element, are assessed on value for money, deliverability and feasibility, as well as the likely outcomes to be achieved.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789996/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T16:21:10.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789996/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789996/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-15","Community Relations: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 7 November 2017 to Question 107852, on community relations: religion, what the criteria are for the allocation of funds to religious organisations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","113312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789997","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-23","<p>Such decisions are taken by Ministers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789997/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T16:22:44.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789997/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789997/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-15","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2017 to Question 111169, on fire prevention, who in his Department is responsible for decisions on the publication of that correspondence.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","113310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789998","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-20","<p>No specific assessment has been made of this issue but this Government is committed to preventing and reducing homelessness across the board. That is why we are aiming to halve rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminate it altogether by 2027. We are investing over £950 million to reduce homelessness and rough sleeping in England by 2020 following the 2015 Spending Review. This includes £10 million of Social Impact Bond funding to support single homeless people with the most complex needs, such as mental health, substance or alcohol misuse.</p><p>We are taking action by implementing the most ambitious legislative reform in decades, the Homelessness Reduction Act, in April 2018, which will ensure that more people get the help they need earlier, to prevent them from becoming homeless in the first place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789998/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:11:56.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789998/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789998/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-15","Homelessness: Mortality Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of cheap, super-strength alcohol on rates of mortality among people who are homeless.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","113327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789999","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>No such meetings have taken place. Financial support for individual athletes is made through the Lottery-funded Athlete Performance Awards which serve to contribute to meeting the athlete’s ordinary living costs and their personal sporting costs, and are awarded on an annual basis subject to a number of criteria including athletes' level of performance.</p><p> </p><p>As promised in the Sporting Future strategy, Government commissioned an independent report by Baroness Grey-Thompson on the Duty of Care owed by sport to its participants. That report was published in April and covered a range of issues relating to elite and grassroots sport. UK Sport is ​currently considering that report in the context of making improvements to the high performance system.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789999/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:01:04.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789999/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789999/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, which groups she has met to discuss pension and workplace rights for elite GB athletes who receive UK Sport or National Lottery funding; and when those meetings took place.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","113333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790000","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>We do not intend to hold discussions with the British Olympic Association (BOA), an independent organisation, ​about​ renaming the Olympic team from Team GB to Team UK. The BOA is responsible for the trading name and branding of the Olympic team representing Great Britain and Northern Ireland, the Isle of Man, the Channel Islands and the UK Overseas Territories.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790000/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:15:21.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790000/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790000/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Olympic Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will discuss with the British Olympic Association renaming the Olympic Team from Team GB to Team UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","113358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790001","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-21","<p>Responsibility for the department's main corporate social media channels is shared across the communications team, as part of its wider news and communications remit and day to day work. Other teams across the department also manage their own policy-specific social media accounts.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790001/answer",,,,,"113533","2017-11-21T17:53:40.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790001/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790001/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many people in her Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790002","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-23","<p>Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Ministers have regular discussions with representatives from the major social media companies which cover a wide range of issues</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial meetings are published quarterly on the Gov.uk website.</p><p>The DCMS Select Committee investigation into fake news is also a vital part of our response to fake news and disinformation. The findings and recommendations of this enquiry will be announced in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790002/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:38:28.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790002/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790002/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Disinformation: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with social media companies on spending through Russian-linked accounts designed to influence the (a) 2016 EU referendum and (b) 2017 General Election.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","113254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790003","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>Ministers from the Department of Digital, Culture, Media and Sport have regular meetings with their ministerial colleagues on a range of issues.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790003/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:08:41.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790003/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790003/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Social Media: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what meetings she has had with Cabinet colleagues on the role of social media platforms in alleged Russian interference in the 2016 EU Referendum.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","113335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790004","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-23","<p>Officials in my Department have had a number of meetings with representatives of Twitter and Facebook to discuss a wide range of issues.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790004/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:26:56.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790004/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790004/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Social Media: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with representatives from (a) Twitter and (b) Facebook on controlling troll and fake accounts used to influence the democratic process in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790005","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Conservative manifesto stated Government would introduce a Cultural Development Fund to use cultural investment to turn around communities, and we will set out further details in due course.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790005/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T13:29:03.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790005/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790005/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Culture: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she plans to establish a Cultural Development Fund to use cultural investment for community regeneration.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","113204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790006","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>The table below provides information taken from Sport England's Active People Survey for the period October 2011 to October 2016. It shows the percentage of adults who volunteered in a coaching role. It should be noted this includes all volunteer sports coaches and not just those volunteering in sports club or, more specifically, a youth sports club.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011/12 (APS6)</p></td><td><p>4.24%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13 (APS7)</p></td><td><p>3.83%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14 (APS8)</p></td><td><p>3.96%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15 (APS9)</p></td><td><p>4.18%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16 (APS10)</p></td><td><p>3.77%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Since 2016 people's engagement in sport and physical activity has been measured via the Active Lives Survey. This provides a broader and more nuanced set of data on the different types of physical activity that people take part in, including for the first time ever, activities such walking and types of dance. It now also captures information about sports volunteering.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s sport strategy ‘Sporting Future’ published in December 2015 takes a new approach to volunteering. It recognises the value to volunteers themselves as well as to sports and the importance of recruiting, retaining and rewarding volunteers who are representative of the entire population. Sport England launched their new Volunteering strategy on 1st December 2016 and is investing over £20 million over 4 years (2017 - 21) to support its implementation. The strategy aims to allow more people to engage in all types of volunteering through sport and physical activity. It also seeks to ensure better quality, meaningful volunteering experiences.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790006/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:33:34.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790006/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790006/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Sports: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what information her Department holds on trends in number of volunteer sports coaches supporting youth sports clubs in the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","113205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790007","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>We have made no such assessment. However, DCMS does produce annual estimates of the contributions of all of its sectors (including the Creative Industries, and within that the 'Advertising and Marketing' sub-sector) to the UK economy, measuring their GVA, imports and exports of goods and services, employment, and number of enterprises. These statistics can be found online at https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dcms-sectors-economic-estimates.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790007/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:03:43.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790007/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790007/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-15","Social Media: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has made an assessment of the total advertising spend across social media platforms in the UK in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","113206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790008","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>The safety of the public, our submarine crews, the defence workforce and the protection of the environment remain the Department's priority. Overall, the Defence Nuclear Programme achieves the required standards of nuclear and radiological safety. Nuclear safety has not been compromised.</p><p>The Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator Annual Assurance Reports for the periods 2015-16 and 2016-17 will not be published as it has been assessed to do so would impact national security. This does not prevent the effective management and independent assessment of the Defence Nuclear Programme, nor prevent its duty holders being held to account, but we cannot accept any compromise of our capabilities in the current security climate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790008/answer",,,,,"112915 ; 113221","2017-11-21T14:52:33.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790008/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790008/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons his Department is not planning to publish the annual reports of the Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","113220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790009","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>The safety of the public, our submarine crews, the defence workforce and the protection of the environment remain the Department's priority. Overall, the Defence Nuclear Programme achieves the required standards of nuclear and radiological safety. Nuclear safety has not been compromised.</p><p>The Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator Annual Assurance Reports for the periods 2015-16 and 2016-17 will not be published as it has been assessed to do so would impact national security. This does not prevent the effective management and independent assessment of the Defence Nuclear Programme, nor prevent its duty holders being held to account, but we cannot accept any compromise of our capabilities in the current security climate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790009/answer",,,,,"112915 ; 113220","2017-11-21T14:52:33.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790009/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790009/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the latest reports of the Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator will be made available for Parliamentary scrutiny.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","113221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790010","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-22","<p>Coalition officers, including some from the UK, carry out short term visits to Coalition locations in Syria as part of their duties, to co-ordinate Coalition support and to engage partner forces. They are not engaging directly in ground combat operations. The Coalition's military campaign against Daesh - including the RAF's contribution to airstrikes against Daesh targets - will continue for as long as is necessary to liberate the civilian population from the terrorists' evil rule. That campaign is making excellent progress; local forces have now recaptured more than 90% of the territory that Daesh once controlled across Iraq and Syria.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790010/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:05:54.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790010/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790010/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the extent and nature of British military presence in Syria is; and for how long he plans to continue military operations in that region.","false","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","113160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790011","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-23","<p>Various Defence communications staff have responsibilities to create and post content to social media channels. However this only forms one aspect of their role. Exact figures for staff with responsibility for social media could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790011/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T14:17:04.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790011/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790011/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Ministry of Defence: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people in his Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790012","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Royal Navy regularly reviews its structure to ensure that the Service is optimised to face the demands of the 21st century, while being appropriately balanced to achieve operational requirements, and therefore continues to consider the need to establish new University Royal Navy Units when it is able.</p><p> </p><p>More widely, the Royal Navy also has an on-going engagement plan with UK Universities by the Captain of Naval Recruitment organisation with initiatives such as the Undergraduate Leadership Programme which can provide the opportunity for undergraduates to apply for a six-week placement with the Royal Navy. This forms part of a wider recruitment engagement which aims to increase awareness of the role of the Royal Navy and Royal Marines in support of British interests.</p><p> </p><p>The Army has a total of 15 University Officer Training Corps (UOTC) and two Officer Training Regiments (OTRs), which, although geographically named, cover a number of affiliated universities located across the whole UK. All UOTCs and OTRs welcome enquiries from individuals from any university. Additionally, wider engagement is conducted within universities, by mutual agreement, by the Army’s specialist engagement teams.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Royal Air Force currently has 15 University Air Squadrons (UAS) which incorporate a number of affiliated universities located across a wide catchment area in the UK to ensure maximum visibility and coverage. The RAF welcomes enquiries from individuals or universities wishing to join their local UAS. Additionally, the Royal Air Force is engaged in ongoing focussed engineering recruitment with 37 universities throughout the country to increase awareness of the available opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>The four Defence Technical Undergraduate Scheme Squadrons are geographically dispersed (Newcastle, Loughborough, Birmingham and Southampton) and partnerships extend to seven further universities.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790012/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:00:31.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790012/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790012/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Armed Forces: Universities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how his Department plans to increase engagement with universities where no single service unit exists.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","113268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790013","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-24","<p>The UK is leaving the EU but remains committed to European defence and security.</p><p>The European Defence Agency (EDA) has a central coordinating role between EU Member States, the European Commission, and countries outside the EU (which must have an Administrative Arrangement with the EDA agreed by all participating Member States) in the development of defence capabilities. The level of future UK cooperation with the EDA forms part of the wider EU withdrawal negotiations.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790013/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T13:43:07.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790013/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790013/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","European Defence Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government plans to seek (a) formal participation in the European Defence Agency and (b) attendance at meetings of the Steering Board of that Agency after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","113249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790014","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-23","<p>Decisions on the UK's preferred relationship with the EU Satellite Centre after the UK leaves the EU have yet to be reached. The Ministry of Defence is in discussion with other Government Departments and will not make a decision in isolation.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790014/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T14:14:49.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790014/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790014/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","EU Satellite Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government plans to establish working relations and formal cooperation with the European Union Satellite Centre after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","113248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790015","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>At the request of the Kenyan Defence Forces (KDF), British Army Training Unit Kenya's training has been relocated from Laikipia to the KDF's Archer's Post Training Area. The last two ASKARI STORM exercises have been conducted there, as is the current 3 PARA exercise.</p><p>When the Kenyan election process is complete, we will discuss with the Kenyan Government the location of future training.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790015/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:55:27.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790015/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790015/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Kenya: Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that defence training can continue in Kenya in the event that troops are unable to use his Department's preferred sites in the Laikipia region of Northern Kenya.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","113356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790016","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-23","<p>The strength of the Army Reserve is regularly published by Defence Statistics in the UK Armed Forces monthly service personnel statistics which can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/uk-armed-forces-monthly-service-personnel-statistics-index" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/uk-armed-forces-monthly-service-personnel-statistics-index</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of people recruited into the Army Future Reserve 2020 each month since January 2014 is shown in the attached table .</p><p> </p><p>The table shows total intake and a breakdown of those who joined the Army Reserve either untrained or already trained. Prior to 1 October 2016, Army Reserve trained intake comprised personnel who were Phase 1 and Phase 2 trained. From 1 October 2016 onward, Army Reserve trained intake comprises of personnel who are Phase 1 trained.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790016/answer","Army Future Reserve.docx","Army Future Reserve.docx","Army Future Reserve 2020","Army Future Reserve 2020",,"2017-11-23T14:16:00.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790016/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790016/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people were recruited into the army reserve in each month since January 2014 for which figures are available; and what the total strength was of the army reserve in each of those months.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","113382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790017","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The planned works to resurface the runway at RAF Northolt have not been delayed.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790017/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:58:31.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790017/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790017/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","RAF Northolt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 26 April 2017 to Question 71589, on RAF Northolt, whether planned works to resurface the runway at RAF Northolt have been delayed; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","113429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790018","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence intends to visit units in Northern Ireland in the near future.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790018/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T16:18:22.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790018/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790018/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-15","Military Bases: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will visit Palace Barracks in Holywood, North Down; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","113432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790019","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The <em>'Schools that work for everyone'</em> consultation document recognised that some faiths, including the Catholic Church, have felt unable to open new schools, subject to the 50% cap, through the free school’s route because they say it contravenes religious rules. The Department is considering carefully the results of the consultation and the proposal to remove the 50% cap on faith admissions in faith free schools. We plan to respond on this issue in due course. We value greatly the important role Catholic schools play in our education system and that will continue.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790019/answer",,,,,"113410","2017-11-24T11:55:31.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790019/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790019/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Church Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the removal of the 50 per cent cap on faith-based admissions on the ability of the Catholic Church to open new schools.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","113404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790020","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>We have outlined in Parliament our position on the various proposals in the '<em>Schools that work for everyone</em>' consultation, and will announce further details in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790020/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:13:04.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790020/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790020/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to publish the Government's response to its consultation entitled Schools that work for everyone; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","113409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790021","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The <em>'Schools that work for everyone'</em> consultation document recognised that some faiths, including the Catholic Church, have felt unable to open new schools, subject to the 50% cap, through the free school’s route because they say it contravenes religious rules. The Department is considering carefully the results of the consultation and the proposal to remove the 50% cap on faith admissions in faith free schools. We plan to respond on this issue in due course. We value greatly the important role Catholic schools play in our education system and that will continue.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790021/answer",,,,,"113404","2017-11-24T11:55:31.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790021/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790021/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Church Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the ability of the Catholic Church to offer all Catholic pupils a school place if the 50 per cent cap on faith-based admissions is maintained.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","113410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790022","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The information is not held centrally. Self declared subcontracted data is sent in at aggregated provider level and as such is not able to be split to determine whether it is delivered to London residents or not.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790022/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T10:22:54.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790022/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790022/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Adult Education: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110007, what proportion of the allocation of each of the approved adult education budget providers that deliver in London but are not located in London to London residents that was (a) directly delivered and (b) subcontracted in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","113421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790023","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>We want fair access to a good school place for every pupil. That is why we routinely keep the admissions system under review and seek feedback from stakeholders on the health of the system.</p><p>Any changes to the School Admissions Code will require a full statutory process, including consultation and parliamentary scrutiny. We will consider the appropriate time for making any changes in the context of competing pressures on the parliamentary timetable.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790023/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:15:08.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790023/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790023/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to make the consultation on amending the School Admissions Code available.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","113399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790024","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The Department does not routinely collect this information. We have, however, recently conducted a survey of local councils and are currently preparing the results for publication. They will be available in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790024/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:37:15.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790024/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790024/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Primary Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many times parents have requested that their summer-born child start reception at five since September 2015; and what proportion of those requests were (a) accepted and (b) refused.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","113400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790025","Department for Education","false","2017-11-23","<p>Studying part-time and later in life can bring enormous benefits for individuals, the economy and employers. That is why the Government has taken steps to help hardworking people who want to gain new skills and advance their careers by studying part-time. These measures include offering financial support in the form of loans to cover fees and, from 2018/19, maintenance costs. We have also enshrined in law the need for the new higher education sector regulator, the Office for Students, to have regard for part-time study.</p><p> </p><p>The government will set out further details of the review in due course.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790025/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:47:10.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790025/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790025/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department's review of higher education will include part-time higher education and learning and earning.","false","Biography information for Bim Afolami","Hitchin and Harpenden","Bim Afolami","113390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790026","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>‘Co-funded’ and ‘fully funded’ are terms that refer to how the aims delivered by a training provider are funded. They do not refer to how a provider receives funding allocations.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of training providers will deliver both co-funded and fully-funded provisions.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790026/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T10:25:47.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790026/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790026/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Adult Education: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110007, whether each of the approved adult education budget providers that deliver in London but are not located in London were (a) co-funded or (b) fully-funded in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","113422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790027","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>A full list of adult education budget (AEB) subcontractors for each of the approved AEB providers which deliver in London but are not located in London in 2015-16 is outlined within the attached file.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790027/answer","113424 attachment.xlsx","113424 attachment.xlsx","Adult education budget subcontractors","Adult education budget subcontractors",,"2017-11-24T10:27:58.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790027/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790027/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Adult Education: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110007, if she will list the subcontractors of each of the approved adult education budget providers that deliver in London but are not located in London in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","113424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790028","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>Officials in the Department for Education and Her Majesty’s Treasury have been working together to consider what impact the proposed change will have on the early years budget and the education budget overall.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790028/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:35:19.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790028/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790028/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Primary Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on amending the School Admissions Code to enable summer born children to begin reception at five.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","113398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790029","Department for Education","false","2017-11-21","<p>The decision to dismiss the Chief Executive was taken by Student Loans Company (SLC) following investigations into allegations about aspects of his management and leadership. The SLC and its shareholders expect the highest standards of management and leadership and these were not upheld by Mr Lamey.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790029/answer",,,,,"113368 ; 113370","2017-11-21T12:56:49.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790029/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790029/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Steve Lamey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions the Universities Minister has had with fellow shareholders in the Student Loans Company in the devolved administrations on the circumstances of the dismissal of the chief executive of that company.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","113371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790030","Department for Education","false","2017-11-21","<p>The decision to dismiss the Chief Executive was taken by Student Loans Company (SLC) following investigations into allegations about aspects of his management and leadership. The SLC and its shareholders expect the highest standards of management and leadership and these were not upheld by Mr Lamey.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790030/answer",,,,,"113370 ; 113371","2017-11-21T12:56:49.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790030/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790030/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Steve Lamey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Universities Minister has had discussions with the Minister for the Cabinet Office on the process for disciplinary proceedings instigated against the former chief executive of the Student Loans Company, Steve Lamey.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","113368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790031","Department for Education","false","2017-11-21","<p>There are no plans to publish a copy of this document. Individual performance reports between Student Loans Company and its employees are confidential.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790031/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T12:58:02.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790031/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790031/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Student Loans Company: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish a copy of the performance review of the Student Loans Company and its chief executive which was referred to in the 15 November edition of The Times newspaper.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","113369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790032","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Sefton Central to the answer I gave on 20 November 2017 to 112985: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=112985" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=112985</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790032/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:21:08.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790032/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790032/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Academies: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 13 November 2017 to Question 112004, how many of the 14 requests for direct admission to an academy relating to a looked-after child were granted.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","113347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790033","Department for Education","false","2017-11-21","<p>The decision to dismiss the Chief Executive was taken by Student Loans Company (SLC) following investigations into allegations about aspects of his management and leadership. The SLC and its shareholders expect the highest standards of management and leadership and these were not upheld by Mr Lamey.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790033/answer",,,,,"113368 ; 113371","2017-11-21T12:56:49.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790033/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790033/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Steve Lamey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions the Universities Minister has had with Sir Paul Jenkins on the criteria for his investigation of the allegations made against the former chief executive of the Student Loans Company, Steve Lamey.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","113370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790034","Department for Education","false","2017-11-21","<p>The non-executive members, including the Chair of the Board of the Student Loans Company were appointed by Department for Education Ministers and Ministers in the Devolved Administrations. The appointments were made following open and transparent competition, and the recruitment and appointment processes fully complied with guidance issued by Cabinet Office and the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790034/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T12:54:24.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790034/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790034/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Student Loans Company: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, who appointed the chair and board members of the Student Loans Company; and what the criteria and processes were for those appointments.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","113367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790035","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>Statutory guidance on supporting pupils at school with medical conditions is available to schools online via the gov.uk website. As such, no dedicated funding has been allocated to issuing this guidance to primary or secondary schools.</p><p> </p><p>In July 2017 we announced an additional £1.3bn for schools and high needs across 2018-19 and 2019-20, in addition to the schools’ budget set at Spending Review 2015. This means funding per pupil for schools and high needs will be maintained in real terms for the next two years. Following our announcement in September 2017, for the first time, under the national funding formula, school funding will be distributed based on the individual needs and characteristics of every school in the country.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790035/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:01:09.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790035/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790035/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Pupils: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 November 2017 to Question 110581, on pupils health, how much funding her Department has allocated to issuing guidance on pupils with medical conditions to (a) primary and (b) secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","113311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790036","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>It is not possible to distinguish between (a) technical or (b) non-technical apprenticeships as there is no definition of technical apprenticeship in the Individualised Learner Return. We can provide a breakdown of apprenticeship starts by apprenticeship sector area and age, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650226/201617_Oct_Apps_Level_SSA_And_Framework_Data_Tool_FINAL.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650226/201617_Oct_Apps_Level_SSA_And_Framework_Data_Tool_FINAL.xlsx</a>.</p><p>Overall, there have been over 1.1 million apprenticeship starts since May 2015 and the Government is committed to achieving three million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020.</p><p>We have introduced the Apprenticeship Levy to encourage sustained employer-investment in high quality apprenticeships of all kinds. This will provide £2.45 billion for apprenticeships in England by 2020. Our apprenticeship reforms are the largest changes to apprenticeships the Government has ever made. These changes are investing in the future of millions of people of all ages and from all backgrounds.</p><p>Employers are currently designing new apprenticeships across a broad range of sectors. The Government has also established the employer-led Institute for Apprenticeships to support this and will extend the remit of the Institute to cover college-based technical education from 2018. This will ensure there is a clear route into skilled and technical occupations across a range of sectors, through both apprenticeships and T Levels.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790036/answer",,,,,"113575","2017-11-24T09:58:49.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790036/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790036/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she has taken to increase the number of technical apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Trudy Harrison","Copeland","Trudy Harrison","113319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790037","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>No decisions have yet been made on our future relationship with the European Union (EU) agencies and bodies after leaving the EU. We are seeking a deep and special partnership with the EU. Our relationship with the EU agencies and bodies, including the Education, Audiovisual and Culture Executive Agency, upon exit will be evaluated on this basis.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790037/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T10:52:54.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790037/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790037/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","EU Education, Audiovisual and Culture Executive Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Government plans to seek formal third country participation in the Education, Audiovisual and Culture Executive Agency after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","113247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790038","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>We have made a significant investment in our schools by providing an additional £1.3 billion across 2018-19 and 2019-20, over and above existing plans. As the independent Institute for Fiscal Studies has confirmed, overall funding per pupil will now be maintained in real terms up to 2020. The national funding formula will deliver higher per pupil funding in respect of every school, and every local area.</p><p> </p><p>More schools are currently judged as good or outstanding by Ofsted than ever before. There were 1.8 million more pupils in schools judged to be ‘good’ or ‘outstanding’ in England as of August 2016 compared to August 2010. And the attainment gap between disadvantaged students and those who are better off is closing.</p><p> </p><p>We appreciate teachers’ dedication and hard work and understand that they need to be able to do their job well without sacrificing their personal life or compromising their wellbeing. Removing unnecessary workload for teachers is a priority for this government. We recognised the problem of unnecessary workload when we launched the Workload Challenge in 2014. On 24 February 2017 we published the results of our workload survey and a clear action plan setting out the steps we will take to help tackle this issue, including targeted support for schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790038/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T14:52:58.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790038/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790038/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will carry out and publish an assessment of the effect of changes on levels of funding for schools on (a) well-being of teachers and and (b) school results.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","113256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790039","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>There are five full time staff members in the social media team.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790039/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:32:52.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790039/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790039/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Department for Education: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people in her Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790040","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The number and percentage of children looked after continuously for at least twelve months at 31 March of the year in which key stage 4 assessments were taken who achieved five or more GCSEs at grades A*-C in each year is given in the table below.</p><p>Due to reforms in secondary accountability measures, the numbers and percentages in the table are not directly comparable across years. Notably, there were major changes in the calculation of the performance measures between 2013 and 2014 so we cannot conclude that there is a decline in performance in these years.</p><p><strong>Key stage 4 eligibility and performance of children who have been looked after continuously for at least twelve months<sup>1</sup>, percentage achieving 5+ GCSEs A*-C or equivalent.</strong></p><p>Figures from 2014 onwards are not comparable with those in earlier years due to major reforms in the calculation of key stage 4 performance measures and do not signify a decline in the performance of looked after children<sup>2</sup></p><p>Years: 2010 - 2016<sup>3</sup></p><p>Coverage: England, all schools<sup>4</sup></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number achieving 5+ GCSEs A*-C or equivalent</p></td><td><p>Percentage achieving 5+ GCSEs A*-C or equivalent</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1,430</p></td><td><p>28.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1,680</p></td><td><p>33.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1,810</p></td><td><p>37.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1,810</p></td><td><p>37.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>800</p></td><td><p>16.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015<sup>5</sup></p></td><td><p>910</p></td><td><p>18.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>890</p></td><td><p>18.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><em>Source: CLA-NPD matched data</em></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>1. Children looked after continuously for at least twelve months as at 31 March excluding those children in respite care. Only children who have been matched to key stage 4 data have been included.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>2. In 2013/14, two major reforms were implemented which affect the calculation of key stage 4 performance measures data: 1) Professor Alison Wolf’s Review of Vocational Education recommendations which: restrict the qualifications counted; prevent any qualification from counting as larger than one GCSE; and cap the number of non-GCSEs included in performance measures at two per pupil, and 2) an early entry policy to only count a pupil’s first attempt at a qualification, in subjects counted in the English Baccalaureate.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>3. Figures for 2016 are based on amended attainment data. Figures for all other years are based on final data. Including entries and achievements in previous academic years.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>4. Includes pupils in state-funded schools (academies, free schools, city technology colleges, further education colleges with provision for 14- to 16-year-olds and state-funded specials schools), independent schools, independent special schools, non-maintained special schools, hospital schools and alternative provision (including pupil referral units, AP free schools and AP academies as well as state-funded AP placements in other institutions).</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>5. Since September 2014, general further education colleges and sixth-form colleges have been able to directly enrol 14- to 16-year-olds. 2014/15 was the first year in which these colleges have pupils at the end of key stage 4 and are included in the data. Early entry policy extended to all subjects.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Numbers have been rounded to the nearest 10. Percentages have been rounded to one decimal place.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790040/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:31:09.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790040/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790040/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","GCSE: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of looked-after children achieved five or more GCSEs at grades A* to C in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","113316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790041","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The Network of Excellence for Computer Science Teaching is a Department for Education funded programme which provides high-quality CPD to existing teachers in England. Funding will total £5.8 million between 2012 and 2018.</p><p> </p><p>There are over 350 trained Master Teachers in the Network of Excellence for Computer Science Teaching in England. Schools can commission them to provide bespoke training for their teachers.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790041/answer",,,,,"113298","2017-11-24T12:18:03.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790041/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790041/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","ICT: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding has been allocated to the national network of Master Teachers for Computing.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","113297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790042","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The Network of Excellence for Computer Science Teaching is a Department for Education funded programme which provides high-quality CPD to existing teachers in England. Funding will total £5.8 million between 2012 and 2018.</p><p> </p><p>There are over 350 trained Master Teachers in the Network of Excellence for Computer Science Teaching in England. Schools can commission them to provide bespoke training for their teachers.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790042/answer",,,,,"113297","2017-11-24T12:18:03.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790042/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790042/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","ICT: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teachers are part of the national network of Master Teachers for Computing.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","113298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790043","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The majority of the Department’s capital budget is allocated to local councils and other responsible bodies through basic need and school condition allocations, with decisions on investment taken locally. The Department’s total capital budget for education – which includes investment in all types of school – in each year since 2010-11 is set out below.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Department for Education capital spend, 2010-11 to 2016-17, £ billions</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7.1</p></td><td><p>5.0</p></td><td><p>4.6</p></td><td><p>4.1</p></td><td><p>4.8</p></td><td><p>5.1</p></td><td><p>5.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Sources:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630518/DfE_Consolidated_annual_report_and_accounts_2016-17_print.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630518/DfE_Consolidated_annual_report_and_accounts_2016-17_print.pdf</a>.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/517766/DfE-consolidated-annual-report-and-a-counts-2014-to-2015-Web-version.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/517766/DfE-consolidated-annual-report-and-a-counts-2014-to-2015-Web-version.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790043/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T11:39:41.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790043/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790043/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Academies: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the value of capital investment in academies, free schools and university technical colleges has been in each year from 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790044","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>Funding allocations are not split by the type of provision they are intended to provide.</p><p> </p><p>Instead, each training provider is allocated an Adult Education Budget which they are entitiled to use for skills they wish to invest in and develop.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790044/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T09:34:25.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790044/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790044/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","English Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department allocated for English for speakers of other languages lessons for each Greater Manchester authority in each year from 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790045","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The department is carefully considering the results of the Schools that work for everyone consultation and the proposal to remove the 50% cap. We plan to respond on this issue in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790045/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T08:43:56.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790045/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790045/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what timescale she has set for replacing inclusivity rules relating to faith schools, including Roman Catholic schools.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","113156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790046","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>Custody should be a last resort and only imposed after the court has considered alternative sentences to be served in the community. We are committed to making sure that as many women as possible are effectively rehabilitated in the community to better protect the public and deliver better outcomes for female offenders.</p><p>This department has not made any assessment of the effect of maternal imprisonment on a child’s emotional development. However, the government has funded a contract worth over £1.4m for Barnardo’s to operate the <em>i-HOP</em> service to share evidence on practice and advise commissioners and practitioners on the options available to support the families of offenders.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790046/answer",,,,,"113209","2017-11-20T17:12:32.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790046/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790046/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Mothers: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on steps to reduce the number of children separated from their mothers and families through maternal imprisonment.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","113210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790047","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The Department collects information from each local authority on the number of schools, the number of places in those schools and the number of pupils on roll through the annual school capacity survey (SCAP). The Department does not collect school capacity information at parliamentary constituency level.</p><p>Data relating to the position in the 2016/17 academic year will be published in the new year. Data for previous years can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-capacity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-capacity</a>.</p><p>Table A, attached, shows the number of primary schools in South Tyneside and the North East which are (i) full and (ii) have one or more pupils in excess of capacity, every year since 2010.</p><p>Table B, attached, shows the number of secondary schools in South Tyneside and the North East which are (i) full and (ii) have one or more pupils in excess of capacity, every year since 2010.</p><p>The Department does not have a measure for over-subscription. The admissions and offers process is run by the local authorities who are responsible for ensuring that the admissions criteria are applied for all schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790047/answer","113196 + 113195 attachment.xlsx","113196 + 113195 attachment.xlsx","Tables","Tables","113196","2017-11-24T14:53:40.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790047/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790047/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Secondary Education: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many secondary schools in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside and (c) the North East were classified as (i) full and (ii) oversubscribed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","113195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790048","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>The Department collects information from each local authority on the number of schools, the number of places in those schools and the number of pupils on roll through the annual school capacity survey (SCAP). The Department does not collect school capacity information at parliamentary constituency level.</p><p>Data relating to the position in the 2016/17 academic year will be published in the new year. Data for previous years can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-capacity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-capacity</a>.</p><p>Table A, attached, shows the number of primary schools in South Tyneside and the North East which are (i) full and (ii) have one or more pupils in excess of capacity, every year since 2010.</p><p>Table B, attached, shows the number of secondary schools in South Tyneside and the North East which are (i) full and (ii) have one or more pupils in excess of capacity, every year since 2010.</p><p>The Department does not have a measure for over-subscription. The admissions and offers process is run by the local authorities who are responsible for ensuring that the admissions criteria are applied for all schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790048/answer","113196 + 113195 attachment.xlsx","113196 + 113195 attachment.xlsx","Tables","Tables","113195","2017-11-24T14:53:40.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790048/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790048/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Primary Education: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many primary schools in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside and (c) the North East were classified as (i) full and (ii) oversubscribed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","113196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790049","Department for Education","false","2017-11-24","<p>In July 2017 we announced an additional £1.3 billion for schools and high needs across 2018-19 and 2019-20, in addition to the schools budget set at Spending Review 2015. This means funding per pupil for schools and high needs will be maintained in real terms for the next two years.</p><p> </p><p>Nothing in legislation prevents a school from asking for voluntary contributions for the benefit of the school or any school activities and this is a matter for schools. However, no parent is required to make a contribution to their child’s education. The rules are clear and no policies have been introduced by this government to allow schools to charge for education provided during school hours and this includes the supply of any materials or equipment.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790049/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:10:01.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790049/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790049/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Schools: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her policies of the finding in the London Councils' Ask the Parents: the Fifth Year Survey, published in November 2017, that 35 per cent of parents in London have been asked to make financial contributions to their school.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","113219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790050","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>Custody should be a last resort and only imposed after the court has considered alternative sentences to be served in the community. We are committed to making sure that as many women as possible are effectively rehabilitated in the community to better protect the public and deliver better outcomes for female offenders.</p><p>This department has not made any assessment of the effect of maternal imprisonment on a child’s emotional development. However, the government has funded a contract worth over £1.4m for Barnardo’s to operate the <em>i-HOP</em> service to share evidence on practice and advise commissioners and practitioners on the options available to support the families of offenders.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790050/answer",,,,,"113210","2017-11-20T17:12:32.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790050/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790050/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Mothers: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department has made an assessment of the effect of maternal imprisonment on a child's emotional development; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","113209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790051","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>Like all departments, the Secretary of State for Education is planning for a number of EU Exit scenarios to make sure we are ready on Day 1.</p><p>We have reprioritised during this financial year as necessary, whilst the costs of EU Exit in 2018-19 and 2019-20 will be affected by negotiations over the coming months.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790051/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:14:04.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790051/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790051/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-15","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what contingency funding her Department has allocated in relation to the Government's negotiations on the UK leaving the EU for the  (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20 financial years.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","113181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790052","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-20","<p>Like all departments, Defra is planning for a number of scenarios for the UK’s departure from the EU to make sure we are ready on Day 1. Over £250m of additional funding has been approved across a number of departments in 2017/18 to prepare for Brexit. Defra has received additional funding this year, and has reprioritised to meet new pressures arising from Brexit preparations. The additional funding received from the Reserve for 2017/8 will be set out at Supplementary Estimates. The costs of EU Exit in 2018-19 and 2019-20 financial years will be affected by negotiations over the coming months and will be agreed with HM Treasury in early 2018.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790052/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:29:32.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790052/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790052/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what contingency funding his Department has allocated in relation to the Government's negotiations on the UK leaving the EU for the (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20 financial years.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","113180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790053","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-21","<p>Defra and the Environment Agency have received a number of representations on Environment Agency decisions on definition of waste panel assessments. Responses are tailored to individual cases.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790053/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T11:04:09.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790053/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790053/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Business: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations his Department has received relating to Environment Agency decisions on definition of waste panel assessments; and what responses have been made to those representations.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","113239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790054","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Government is committed to continuing to work with the industry to make the transition to peat alternatives and to overcome the barriers to their use. For example, we are jointly funding research with the industry, which includes commercial scale demonstration trials, to overcome barriers to peat replacement in professional horticulture. We have also worked with the industry to develop a Responsible Sourcing Scheme for Growing Media which allows manufacturers and retailers to make informed choices on growing media inputs to amateur/retail products, based on environmental and social impacts. We are continuing to support the industry as they put this scheme into practice.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790054/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:42:37.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790054/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790054/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Horticulture: Peat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to increase the use of peat replacement products for professional and amateur horticulture.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","113240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790055","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>As part of our planning for the UK’s exit from the EU we are developing a 25 Year Environment Plan and a renewed strategy on resources and waste. Officials are developing the plans for engagement with businesses, and views on the key barriers to resource efficiency and ideas for addressing these will be welcome.</p><p> </p><p>The online IsItWaste tool for self-assessment for the definition of waste currently has 981 assessments registered. This is cumulative since 2013. It would not include any self-assessments later deleted by the customer.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency does not have information or data about the impact on investment in the waste sector from the temporary closure of the Definition of Waste panel.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790055/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T10:52:56.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790055/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790055/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Business: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to remove barriers to a more resource-efficient economy; what evidence there is that businesses are using the online tool for self-assessment for definition of waste; whether the closure of the Definition of Waste panel has impacted investment in the sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","113241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790056","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-22","<p>Giant hogweed (<em>Heracleum mantegazzianum</em>) is an invasive non-native species with established populations in the UK. It is an offence under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 to plant or otherwise cause giant hogweed to grow in the wild.</p><p> </p><p>Giant hogweed was added as a species of Union concern under the EU Invasive Alien Species Regulation in August 2017. Species of Union concern cannot be imported, kept, bred, transported, sold, used or exchanged, allowed to reproduce, grown or cultivated, or released into the environment. Under the Regulation, Member States are required to set out measures to manage species of Union concern that are widespread in their territory within 18 months of listing. The government will be consulting on management plans for giant hogweed and other species of Union concern that are widespread in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Community protection notices made under the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 are also being used by local authorities and the Police to tackle the impact to their communities of invasive non-native species including giant hogweed. The Home Office guidance on using community protection notices to tackle invasive non-native plants can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nonnativespecies.org/downloadDocument.cfm?id=1176" target="_blank">www.nonnativespecies.org//downloadDocument.cfm?id=1176</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Local Action Groups, with support from Government, are actively involved in reducing and eradicating giant hogweed. A new EU co-funded project, totalling €1.1 million, will develop a regional approach to tackling invasive non-native species, supporting Local Action Groups in a co-ordinated approach.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790056/answer",,,,,"113271","2017-11-22T12:32:15.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790056/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790056/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Giant Hogweed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to reduce to prevalence of giant hogweed in the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","113270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790057","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-22","<p>The effectiveness of the Act is assessed annually by recording details of complaints and enforcement cases. Research undertaken for Defra in 2014 concluded that ragwort is not becoming more widespread.</p><p> </p><p>The Weeds Act 1959 gives us the power to arrange for the clearance of the plant and to recover the cost from the land occupier. Natural England (the delegated authority for investigating complaints about injurious weeds) engages with inspectors from the Rural Payments Agency to investigate formal complaints raised to them, and enforce weed clearance where the landowner has not taken adequate action to control ragwort.</p><p> </p><p>Enforcement is a last resort and where possible we encourage communications between landowners and complainants to try and resolve the issue. In the vast majority of cases, this approach is successful. All complaints so far have been resolved without requiring prosecution, either voluntarily by the landowner or after an enforcement order has been made.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790057/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T11:51:18.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790057/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790057/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Ragwort Control Act 2003","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Ragwort Control  Act 2003 in limiting the spread of ragwort; how many successful prosecutions have been brought under that act; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","113217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790058","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-22","<p>Japanese knotweed was first introduced into the UK in the early 19th century and is now widespread here and throughout most of Europe. It is not considered feasible to eradicate Japanese knotweed entirely from the UK but, with persistence, isolated populations can be eradicated. It is an offence under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 to plant or otherwise cause Japanese knotweed to grow in the wild.</p><p> </p><p>Defra continues to fund a biocontrol programme through the release of a psyllid insect to tackle Japanese knotweed. If successful, the psyllid will not eradicate Japanese knotweed but should in time reduce its invasive capacity as well as the effort and cost of managing it. This year, around 120,000 psyllids will be released at 16 sites in England and Wales using new methods designed to improve the likelihood that the psyllid will establish in the wild.</p><p> </p><p>Local Action Groups, with support from government, are actively involved in reducing and eradicating Japanese knotweed. For example, the New Forest Non-Native Plants Project and the Medway Valley Countryside Partnership have controlled Japanese knotweed on 49 separate sites this year. A new EU co-funded project, totalling €1.1 million, will develop a regional approach to tackling invasive non-native species, supporting Local Action Groups in a co-ordinated approach.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England and the Environment Agency also undertake action nationally to remove Japanese knotweed where it is affecting protected sites, water quality or adds to the risk of flooding.</p><p> </p><p>Community protection notices made under the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 are also being used by local authorities and the Police to tackle the impact to their communities of invasive non-native species including Japanese knotweed. The Home Office guidance on using community protection notices to tackle invasive non-native plants can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nonnativespecies.org/downloadDocument.cfm?id=1176" target="_blank">www.nonnativespecies.org//downloadDocument.cfm?id=1176</a></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790058/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T10:53:02.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790058/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790058/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Japanese Knotweed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made in eliminating Japanese knotweed in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","113218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790059","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-20","<p>There are currently 309 subscribers to the UK-Air email bulletin service.</p><p> </p><p>The UK-Air Twitter account currently has 6,697 followers. The average engagement rate for Tweets made from the Defra UK-Air Twitter account between 1 November 2016 and 31 October 2017 was 0.7%.</p><p> </p><p>A five day forecast of predicted air pollution levels is continually updated on the UK-Air website, along with advice from Public Health England to allow members of the public, particularly those who are most likely to be affected by air pollution, to plan and take action.</p><p> </p><p>Defra also issues email alerts to the health charity network during periods of elevated air pollution. These alerts provide full details of the nature of the air pollution episode along with links to further information, including specific health advice relevant to the episode.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790059/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:14:19.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790059/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790059/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have signed up to receive his Department's UK-Air email updates; and what the average engagement rate is for Tweets made from the @DefraUKAir Twitter account.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","113164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790060","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-27","<p>The number of staff in my department employed with a responsibility for social media is three. They are all employed on a full-time basis.</p><p> </p><p>Recent digital campaigns the team have worked on include:</p><ul><li>Protecting your backyard flocks from bird flu and bird flu incident messaging (Jan to March), which reached over 600,000 poultry stakeholders and smallholders on Facebook and Twitter.</li><li>Supporting the evaluation of Environment Agency’s ‘Flood Aware’ campaign and flood incident communications.</li><li>Ongoing biosecurity campaigns providing advice to travellers as to what they can bring back into the country (‘Know Before You Go’ in conjunction with the Home Office), information on Pet passports and basic water biosecurity to water sports hobbyists (Check Clean Dry)</li><li>Asian hornet alert to beekeepers in the south west, and encouraging all beekeepers to download APHA/Non-Native Invasive Species Secretariat Asian hornet app</li></ul>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790060/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-27T15:41:31.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790060/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790060/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people in his Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790061","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-22","<p>Giant hogweed (<em>Heracleum mantegazzianum</em>) is an invasive non-native species with established populations in the UK. It is an offence under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 to plant or otherwise cause giant hogweed to grow in the wild.</p><p> </p><p>Giant hogweed was added as a species of Union concern under the EU Invasive Alien Species Regulation in August 2017. Species of Union concern cannot be imported, kept, bred, transported, sold, used or exchanged, allowed to reproduce, grown or cultivated, or released into the environment. Under the Regulation, Member States are required to set out measures to manage species of Union concern that are widespread in their territory within 18 months of listing. The government will be consulting on management plans for giant hogweed and other species of Union concern that are widespread in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Community protection notices made under the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 are also being used by local authorities and the Police to tackle the impact to their communities of invasive non-native species including giant hogweed. The Home Office guidance on using community protection notices to tackle invasive non-native plants can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nonnativespecies.org/downloadDocument.cfm?id=1176" target="_blank">www.nonnativespecies.org//downloadDocument.cfm?id=1176</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Local Action Groups, with support from Government, are actively involved in reducing and eradicating giant hogweed. A new EU co-funded project, totalling €1.1 million, will develop a regional approach to tackling invasive non-native species, supporting Local Action Groups in a co-ordinated approach.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790061/answer",,,,,"113270","2017-11-22T12:32:15.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790061/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790061/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Giant Hogweed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what advice he has given to local authorities about the control or removal of giant hogweed on land near to public rights of ways or where its presence is likely to have a detrimental effect on the public's health.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","113271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790062","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Environment Agency has worked with partners, in particular Public Health England who operate air monitoring equipment in the UK, to assess any effects on the environment. Air monitoring has not detected any elevated levels of ruthenium 106. Therefore there is no indication of any effects on the environment in the UK.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790062/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T10:57:52.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790062/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790062/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the UK environment of recent reports of radioactive pollution, including traces of ruthenium 106 detected in France, spreading from Eastern Europe.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","113355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790063","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-23","<p>In response to the AMR Review chaired by Lord Jim O’Neill (May 2016), the government set a target to reduce the overall veterinary use of antibiotics in UK livestock from 62 mg/kg (2014 data) to 50 mg/kg by 2018. The government also committed to working with the livestock industry to set sector specific targets for further reductions in future veterinary antibiotic usage. The intention for the sector targets was that future reductions should be greatest where there was most scope, while safeguarding animal health and welfare.</p><p> </p><p>The government’s Veterinary Antibiotic Sales and Surveillance Report published by the Veterinary Medicines Directorate in October 2017 shows sales of antibiotics for use in food-producing animals has dropped by 27%, from 62 mg/kg in 2014 to 45mg/kg in 2016, surpassing the government’s target of 50 mg/kg two years ahead of schedule.</p><p> </p><p>Also in October, veterinary professionals and the livestock industry published stretching targets for a reduction in antibiotic usage in the following sectors: beef, dairy, egg, fish, gamebird, pig, poultry and sheep. The targets were developed in collaboration with government and are centred around the principle that ‘prevention is better than cure’. They are available here: <a href="http://www.ruma.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/RUMA-Targets-Task-Force-Report-2017-FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.ruma.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/RUMA-Targets-Task-Force-Report-2017-FINAL.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>To date the meat poultry section is leading the way with a 71% reduction in antibiotic usage between 2012 and 2016, whilst achieving an 11% increase in productivity over the same period.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790063/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T17:18:12.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790063/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790063/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Livestock: Antibiotics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage farming methods which reduce the use of antibiotics.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","113362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790064","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-21","<p>We have no plans for a ban on third party sellers. We are taking steps to ensure more robust licensing of pet sellers. To that end, new regulations on animal activity licensing will set statutory minimum welfare standards for all commercial pet sellers in England that the local authority must apply when considering whether to issue a licence.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790064/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T16:04:49.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790064/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790064/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Cats and Dogs: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to prohibit the third party sale of puppies and kittens.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","113426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790065","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-21","<p>As announced on 30 September, a bill to increase the maximum penalty for animal cruelty offences to five years imprisonment will be published for consultation around the turn of the year. We will welcome comments from animal welfare charities who have campaigned for this change.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790065/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T13:56:18.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790065/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790065/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what timetable the Government has set for introducing legislation to increase the maximum sentence for animal cruelty offences to five years' imprisonment.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","113378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790066","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-22","<p>Alternatives to culling chicks at one-day old are currently being explored. The University of Leipzig in Germany is developing a new method for in-ovo gender identification, so that eggs identified as male can be sorted and used for purposes other than hatching. This issue was the subject of discussion at a G7 meeting of Farming Ministers in Japan in 2016, where I supported the work and offered UK assistance to build on any results. We will look carefully at the results of this work and how it can be applied to the UK’s poultry industry.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790066/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T13:03:38.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790066/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790066/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-15","Poultry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to promote in-ovo gender identification techniques in the poultry industry in the UK.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","113375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790067","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-21","<p>​We are aware of reports that over 100 Baha'i owned shops and businesses were forced to close for observing Baha'i holy days and, in particular, for observing the bicentenary of the birth of Baha'u'llah earlier this year. Reports estimate that there have been over 1,170 incidents of economic suppression against Iranian Baha'is since 2005. The British Government calls on Iran to respect the rights and freedoms of all its citizens no matter what their religion or belief.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790067/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T16:43:31.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790067/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790067/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports his Department has received on the rate at which the Iranian Government has forced Baha'i shops and businesses to be sealed; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","113420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790068","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-21","<p>The treatment of the Baha'i community in Iran is of particular concern. This includes recent reports of an increased number of Baha'i students being expelled from university, as well as the denial of access to higher education for adherents of the Baha'i faith, and reports of students being forced to renounce their faith in order to further their education. The British Government supports the UN Special Rapporteur's assessment that discrimination against the Baha'i community in Iran is aggravated by lack of recognition for the Baha'i faith in the Iranian constitution. We call on Iran to respect the rights and freedoms of all its citizens no matter what their religion or belief.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790068/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T16:41:44.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790068/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790068/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has received reports on an increase in the number of expulsions of Baha'i university students in Iran since June 2017, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","113419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790069","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-21","<p>There has been no ministerial contact with the Zimbabwean Government. Officials met the Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and senior military figures in the Ministry of Defence, including the Commander of the Zimbabwe Defence Forces, on 15 November.​​​</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790069/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T15:29:29.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790069/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790069/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with (a) his Zimbabwean counterpart and (b) the Commander of the Zimbabwean Defence Force on maintaining peace and stability in Zimbabwe.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","113437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790070","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>The UK has longstanding concerns about Iranian involvement in Yemen, which we have raised with the Iranian Government. The Foreign Secretary will discuss a variety of regional and bilateral issues with his counterparts on any future visit to Iran. I made a statement on 9 November expressing concerns about reports that Iran has provided the Houthis with ballistic missiles, which threaten regional security and prolong the conflict.​​</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790070/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:59:27.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790070/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790070/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790070/answer/previousversion/23765","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Yemen: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will discuss the matter of arms smuggling into Yemen with his Iranian counterpart during his forthcoming visit to that country.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","113415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790071","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>We recognise Saudi Arabia's legitimate need to protect its national security following the attempted 4 November missile attack on Riyadh. At the same time, as our statement of 15 November made clear, it is vital that Yemen remains open to humanitarian and commercial access. We call for the immediate resumption of UN flights and the reopening of Hodeidah port. We have engaged with the Saudi Arabian Government at the highest levels on this issue since the 4 November incident and will continue to do so. We are also closely engaged with the UAE and other regional and international partners.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790071/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:53:04.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790071/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790071/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790071/answer/previousversion/23763","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Yemen: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Saudi-led coalition on re-opening Sana'a International Airport in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","113331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790072","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has made payments to Adam Smith International as below:</p><p>Year: Amount (£m)</p><p>2012: 1.9 <br>2013: 3.5 <br>2014: 2.9 <br>2015: 19.3 <br>2016: 35.8</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790072/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:49:53.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790072/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790072/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Adam Smith International: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has provided to Adam Smith International in each year from 2012 to 2016.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","113259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790073","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office encourages all staff to make full use of the opportunities provided by social media support the delivery of FCO objectives as outlined in FCO social media guidance published on GOV.UK.</p><p>There is a small digital team In London whose roles include producing communications material for social media, providing consular assistance online, training and evaluation as well as other communications tasks.</p><p>Overseas small digital hubs in five locations provide training and advice in effective use of social media as part of their work. Communication roles at Post, as well as those of Heads and Deputy Heads of Mission, and various operation roles will often have some responsibility for using social media as part of their work where using digital comms helps deliver our objectives.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790073/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T16:40:43.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790073/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790073/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people in his Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790074","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>​The Russian authorities are well aware of our concerns, as set out by the Prime Minister on 13 November. I am travelling to Russia before the end of the year, where I will have the opportunity to raise this issues in person.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790074/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T16:46:08.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790074/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790074/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Russia: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Russia on social media propaganda targeted at the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790075","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Government is deeply concerned by the treatment of the Rohingya of Rakhine State, following the military's violent operation that prompted more than 600,000 Rohingya people to flee into Bangladesh. The Foreign Secretary has spoken to State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi three times since the start of the crisis, most recently on 21 October, to make clear this situation is completely unacceptable, and to call on her to resolve the crisis. The Minister for Asia and the Pacific pressed Burma's Defence Minister to ensure accountability for the perpetrators of human rights violations when they met on 20 November.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790075/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T17:51:03.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790075/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790075/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Burmese counterpart on ethnic cleansing of Muslim refugees in Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790076","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>​The UK has consistently called on the Government of Bangladesh at official and Ministerial level to grant the Rohingya community in Bangladesh formal refugee status. The Minister for Asia and the Pacific raised this point when he met the Bangladesh High Commissioner Nazmul Quaunine and the B​angladesh Foreign Secretary Shahidul Haque on 2 November. He also visited Bangladesh on 27 and 28 September.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790076/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T17:48:38.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790076/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790076/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Bangladesh on offering Muslim refugees fleeing Myanmar secured settlement.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790077","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Prime Minister made a Written Ministerial Statement on 15 September 2016 informing Parliament that the Government would consider what changes could be made to the Consolidated Guidance to address points made by Sir Mark Waller, the then Intelligence Services Commissioner. This work has been taken forward and the Government will seek the views of the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament on it in the context of their wider Detainee Inquiry.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790077/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:51:34.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790077/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790077/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Intelligence Services: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress the Government has made on considering how to revise the Consolidated Guidance to Intelligence Officers and Service Personnel on the Detention and Interviewing of Detainees Overseas, and on the Passing and Receipt of Intelligence Relating to Detainees.","false","Biography information for Mr Kenneth Clarke","Rushcliffe","Mr Kenneth Clarke","113214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790078","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>​The Cabinet Office, Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Home Office and Ministry of Defence as well as the security and intelligence agencies, National Crime Agency and SO15 have been fully involved in the work to consider what changes could be made to the Consolidated Guidance. The Government will seek the views of the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament on it in the context of their wider Detainee Inquiry.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790078/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:52:43.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790078/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790078/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Intelligence Services: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which Government Departments, parliamentary committees and civil society groups the Government plans to consult on revisions to the Consolidated Guidance to Intelligence Officers and Service Personnel on the Detention and Interviewing of Detainees Overseas, and on the Passing and Receipt of Intelligence Relating to Detainees.","false","Biography information for Mr Kenneth Clarke","Rushcliffe","Mr Kenneth Clarke","113215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790079","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Foreign Secretary has had no formal meetings with representatives of Conservative Friends of Israel in this period.​ The Foreign Secretary meets members and staff of Conservative Friends of Israel from time to time in the course of his normal business, as he does many other organisations.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790079/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T14:01:19.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790079/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790079/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Conservative Friends of Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings he has had with representatives of the Conservative Friends of Israel since January 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","113242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790080","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-21","<p>The UK is committed to supporting the Palestinian Authority (PA) and strengthening UK-Palestinian relations. The UK’s long-standing policy on the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) is to support a negotiated settlement leading to a viable and sovereign Palestinian state living alongside a safe and secure Israel. We are planning to provide £56 million in funding to the OPTs in FY 2017/18, helping to lay the foundation for the development of a future Palestinian state by fostering the development of the necessary state institutions. UK support helps to maintain stability, and supports the PA to act as an effective partner for peace with Israel.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790080/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T16:39:24.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790080/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790080/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Palestinians: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Palestine are for 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","113243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790081","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>British Officials in the High Commission in New Delhi, and in London, regularly engage with the Indian authorities on this case. Officials in the British High Commission in New Delhi have also attended court sessions on the case and will continue to do so. Ministers will raise the case with the Indian Authorities where the opportunities ​arise.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790081/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:53:58.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790081/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790081/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Aman Vyas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made, by whom within his Department, to which organisations in relation to the extradition hearings in India of Aman Vyas between May and November 2017.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","113179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790082","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-22","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth strongly recommends that all UK citizens planning to travel overseas, familiarise themselves with our travel advice. The travel advice pages are regularly reviewed and updated to reflect changing circumstances. We currently advise against all but essential travel to Rivers, Bayelsa and Delta States and against all travel to the riverine areas of those states. We are supporting the families of the four British people who were abducted on 13 October in Nigeria. I would like to offer my condolences to the friends and family of Ian Squire who was tragically killed whilst being held captive. This has clearly been a traumatic time for all concerned, and our staff will continue to do all we can to support the families.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790082/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T14:53:05.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790082/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790082/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Nigeria: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what advice and support his Department is providing to people from the UK, including missionaries and humanitarian workers, who plan to travel to provide support to communities in Nigeria's Delta region.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","113188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790083","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>All FCO programmes conform to the department’s robust management and assurance processes to ensure they deliver value for money for the UK taxpayer.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790083/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T16:14:46.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790083/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790083/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Overseas Aid: Accountability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he plans to take to improve the management, transparency and accountability of his Department's aid budget.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","113191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790084","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>​UN Security Council Resolution 2334 addresses settlements while also calling for an end to incitement and terror. The resolution was passed on 23 December 2016 and asks the Secretary-General to report to the Council every three months on the implementation of its provisions. We are gravely concerned by the increased pace of settlement advancement by the Israeli government in 2017, including plans for the first new settlement deep in the West Bank in more than 25 years, the first new housing units in Hebron for 15 years, and legislation to retroactively approve unauthorised settlement outposts.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790084/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:57:19.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790084/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790084/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790084/answer/previousversion/23755","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the level of compliance by the Israeli Government with UN Security Council Resolution 2334 (2016) on urging an end to Israeli settlements.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","113199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790085","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>There have been no formal proposals from the European Commission on this matter. The UK continues to urge Israel and Egypt to ease movement and access restrictions on Gaza, stressing the damage the restrictions are doing to the living standards of ordinary Gazans. The UK remains committed to supporting vulnerable Gazans, through funding for basic service delivery through the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees and private sector development programmes. We will continue to urge the parties to prioritise progress towards reaching a durable solution for Gaza and to take the necessary practical steps to ensure Gaza’s reconstruction and economic recovery.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790085/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:58:38.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790085/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790085/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790085/answer/previousversion/23757","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Gaza: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support he has given to EU proposals to provide sea access to Gaza.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","113201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790086","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>​The UK’s longstanding position on the Middle East Peace Process is clear: we support a negotiated settlement leading to a safe and secure Israel living alongside a viable and sovereign Palestinian state, based on 1967 borders with agreed land swaps, Jerusalem as the shared capital of both states, and a just, fair, agreed, and realistic settlement for refugees. We will continue to press Israel and the Palestinians strongly on the need to re-enter direct negotiations and refrain from taking actions which make peace more difficult. The Foreign Secretary reiterated the UK’s support for a two-state solution and urged renewed progress on the Middle East Peace Process when he met Prime Minister Netanyahu in London on 2 November.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790086/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:58:58.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790086/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790086/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790086/answer/previousversion/23758","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-15","Middle East: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government means by a two-state solution for Israel and Palestine; and how it plans to help achieve that solution.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","113202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790087","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Secretary of State for Health and the Secretary of State for Transport have many conversations covering a wide-range of issues. The Department has found no record of one-to-one meetings since 8 June 2017.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790087/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:08:37.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790087/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790087/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 7 November 2017 to Question 110811, how many times he has met the Secretary of State for Transport since 8 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","113226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790088","Department of Health","false","2017-11-23","<p>Data are not collected in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790088/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:09:26.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790088/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790088/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Vaccination: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was spent from the public purse on child vaccinations in each year since 2010 to date.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","113147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790089","Department of Health","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Department does not have any members of staff who have social media as their sole responsibility. There is a wide range of people in the department who have some responsibility for social media, including the monitoring of social media activity, as well as posting content on official Departmental channels. Because this responsibility is spread so widely, it means we are not able to give a specific number of full-time or part-time staff who have responsibility for social media.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790089/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:29:39.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790089/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790089/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Department of Health: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in his Department with responsibility for social media are employed on an (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","113283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790090","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The forthcoming joint Department of Health and Department for Education Children and Young People's Mental Health Green Paper will contain further details on this commitment.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790090/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:49:07.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790090/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790090/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has established a target date for all schools to have a single point of contact with NHS CAMHS.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","113337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790091","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Department is committed to ensuring children and young people with mental health conditions can receive treatment as close as possible to where they live.</p><p> </p><p>An out of area placement for children and young people was defined in 2014 by NHS England in its Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services Tier 4 Report as:</p><p> </p><p>“Admissions deemed to be placements where young people are harmed by the distance and disconnection from local services, family and friends”.</p><p> </p><p>It is inappropriate when patients are placed out of area for the reason of non-availability of a local bed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to end inappropriate out of area placement for children and young people by 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>On 31 March 2017, NHS England announced the next steps to ensure children and young people do not have to travel far from home for mental health care. As well as funding between 150 and 180 new beds, we are increasing the availability of services in the community to ensure the right beds are in the right place.</p><p> </p><p>This includes a program of work to improve timely treatments in the community for those needing urgent or emergency assessment as well as the development and recruitment for community eating disorder services.</p><p> </p><p>Source:</p><p> </p><p>Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services Tier 4 Report, NHS England, 2014.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/camhs-tier-4-rep.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/camhs-tier-4-rep.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790091/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:47:14.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790091/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790091/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Out of Area Treatment: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's definition is of an inappropriate out-of-area placement for children; and what plans he has to eliminate the practice of such placements by 2021.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","113338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790092","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Care Quality Commission has recently undertaken a study examining the causes of changing rates of detention, under the Mental Health Act (1983) and are due to publish their findings by the end of the year. The Government has also commissioned an independent review of the Mental Health Act, chaired by Professor Sir Simon Wessely, which will report by autumn 2018.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790092/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:55:16.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790092/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790092/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of whether there is a causal link between the number of inpatient beds decreasing and increases in the number of detentions under the Mental Health Act 1983 in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","113339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790093","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>NHS England inform us that the vision of the West Kent Clinical Commissioning Group and Dartford, Gravesham and Swanley Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is to provide high quality mental health care now, and for future generations. This means enabling everyone who requires interventions to have timely access to the best available treatment. The mental health care pathway spans commissioning organisations including the CCGs and Kent County Council, and includes provision for universal reach, resilience, early intervention, specialist and crisis support.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the CCGs and their partners are on track to meet all ambitions set out in the National Health Service Five Year Forward View for Mental Health. This is monitored through NHS England assurance processes.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790093/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:50:44.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790093/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790093/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Mental Health Services: Kent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the success of mental health care outcomes in the West Kent and Dartford, Gravesham and Swanley areas since 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","113299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790094","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>Diagnosing autism in children can involve a range of observations over time and a number of different professionals. The time taken to formulate a diagnosis will not be the same in all cases.</p><p> </p><p>There are concerns in some local areas that the length of time some children have had to wait for an assessment for autism to begin is longer than the three months recommended by the National Institute for Care and Health Excellence (NICE) guidelines from a referral to a first appointment. Whilst local clinical commissioning groups have been working to bring down the waits in line with the NICE guidelines, to date there has been no national collection of waiting times data.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is taking steps to rectify this and NHS Digital have confirmed they will be collecting and recording waiting times from referral for suspected autism to a first appointment within the Mental Health Services Data Set from April 2018. This will mean that each area can be held to account in real time and action can be taken to support them when waiting times are increasing.</p><p> </p><p>An indicative timeline for the development of care pathways was set out in the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health. The precise timetable for the establishment of a care pathway for autism will be confirmed by NHS England in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790094/answer",,,,,"113301","2017-11-24T12:47:29.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790094/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790094/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Autism: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will review waiting times in paediatric services for autism diagnosis.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","113300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790095","Department of Health","false","2017-11-21","<p>All providers of NHS services are expected to co-operate in providing education and training. The Care Act 2014 strengthened the requirements on all providers to promote and engage with education and training as well as to co-operate with local education and training boards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790095/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T12:29:26.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790095/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790095/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the long-term effect on the training of clinicians of using private sector companies to provide NHS services.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","113343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790096","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>Diagnosing autism in children can involve a range of observations over time and a number of different professionals. The time taken to formulate a diagnosis will not be the same in all cases.</p><p> </p><p>There are concerns in some local areas that the length of time some children have had to wait for an assessment for autism to begin is longer than the three months recommended by the National Institute for Care and Health Excellence (NICE) guidelines from a referral to a first appointment. Whilst local clinical commissioning groups have been working to bring down the waits in line with the NICE guidelines, to date there has been no national collection of waiting times data.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is taking steps to rectify this and NHS Digital have confirmed they will be collecting and recording waiting times from referral for suspected autism to a first appointment within the Mental Health Services Data Set from April 2018. This will mean that each area can be held to account in real time and action can be taken to support them when waiting times are increasing.</p><p> </p><p>An indicative timeline for the development of care pathways was set out in the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health. The precise timetable for the establishment of a care pathway for autism will be confirmed by NHS England in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790096/answer",,,,,"113300","2017-11-24T12:47:29.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790096/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790096/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Paediatrics: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the length of waiting times in paediatric services for diagnosis of suspected autism since 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","113301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790097","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister welcomed the Stevenson/Farmer review, and has accepted the recommendations that apply to the Civil Service and NHS England as employers. The Government will support and encourage the wider public sector in taking forward the recommendations wherever possible.</p><p> </p><p>It is our hope that responsible employers will choose to adopt the mental health core standards and improve their workplace environment, with recommendations for trade bodies, regulators and Government supporting them in making this happen.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will respond to the full review as a part of our response to the consultation on the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper. We plan to publish this later this year.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790097/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:49:03.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790097/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790097/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Mental Health and Employers Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps are being taken to implement the recommendations of the Stevenson/Farmer review and the core and enhanced standards in public life.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","113302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790098","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>As announced by my Rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister on 4 October 2017, the Government will launch a full consultation before the end of this year, on increasing rates of organ donation, including a new “opt out” system of consent for England. The consultation will seek views on:</p><p>- How to increase rates of organ donation, particularly from Black, Asian, and minority ethnic communities;</p><p>- How the issue of consent should be managed within the National Health Service;</p><p>- How technology could help people to discuss their preferences with family; and</p><p>- How opt out could work in practice, the safeguards needed and how families could be supported.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790098/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:44:41.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790098/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790098/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Organs: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on bringing forward proposals to change England's organ donation system from opt in to opt out.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","113303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790099","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Department’s aim is to broadly align entitlement to help with health costs (including free National Health Service prescriptions and free NHS dental treatment) for Universal Credit recipients with those in place for the relevant legacy benefits. This is achieved by passporting Universal Credit recipients to free help with health costs where their income falls below a given earnings threshold.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790099/answer",,,,,"113266","2017-11-20T17:05:26.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790099/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790099/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if fewer or more claimants of universal credit will be eligible for free dental care than were under the legacy benefits systems.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","113265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790100","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Department’s aim is to broadly align entitlement to help with health costs (including free National Health Service prescriptions and free NHS dental treatment) for Universal Credit recipients with those in place for the relevant legacy benefits. This is achieved by passporting Universal Credit recipients to free help with health costs where their income falls below a given earnings threshold.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790100/answer",,,,,"113265","2017-11-20T17:05:26.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790100/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790100/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if fewer or more claimants of universal credit will be eligible for free prescriptions then were under the legacy benefits systems.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","113266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790101","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>There has been extensive work completed by the NHS England Mesh Working Group to investigate the concerns raised in relation to surgical meshes which included exploring if a one-off information gathering exercise on patient outcomes should be conducted. They concluded that this would not be the best allocation of resources to respond to this issue.</p><p> </p><p>Following further discussion with the Parliamentary Under Secretary for Health (Lord O’Shaughnessy) and members of the Surgical Mesh All Party Parliamentary Group on 14 November, NHS England and the Medicines and Health products Regulatory Agency are looking again at this issue and will advise ministers accordingly.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790101/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:16:05.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790101/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790101/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Surgical Mesh Implants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to audit the use of surgical mesh for (a) pelvic organ prolapse and (b) stress urinary incontinence; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","113329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790102","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>It would not be possible to estimate the cost of any inquiry until the form of such an inquiry and its terms of reference were to be established.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790102/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:18:44.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790102/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790102/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Surgical Mesh Implants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse would be of an inquiry into the use of surgical mesh.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","113330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790103","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>We recognise that a small but significant number of people have suffered from some very severe complications as a result of procedures using surgical mesh. Surgical procedures using mesh devices have provided an effective form of treatment in many cases it can be far less invasive than alternative surgical procedures and, unfortunately, there are risks associated with most medical interventions.</p><p> </p><p>Compensation is normally provided on the basis of clinical negligence. There are no plans to allocate funding for further compensation.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790103/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:14:08.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790103/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790103/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Surgical Mesh Implants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to allocate funding to provide compensation to people affected by injuries caused by surgical mesh; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","113326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790104","Department of Health","false","2017-11-23","<p>Changes to overall spending for the West Kent Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) and Dartford, Gravesend and Swanley CCG since 2016 are set out in the tables below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>West Kent Clinical Commissioning Group</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% Mental Health Spend</p></td><td><p>9.32%</p></td><td><p>9.75%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Dartford, Gravesend and Swanley CCG</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% Mental Health Spend</p></td><td><p>6.16%</p></td><td><p>6.49%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790104/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T11:57:41.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790104/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790104/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Mental Health Services: Kent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what change there has been in spending on mental health as a proportion to overall spending since 2016 by the (a) West Kent and (b) Dartford, Gravesham and Swanley clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","113307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790105","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>This data is not collected centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790105/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T12:43:25.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790105/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790105/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Sexual Assault Referral Centres: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting time was at sexual assault referral centres for therapeutic services through referral pathways for children under 18 for each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","113321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790106","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The provision of primary medical services is the responsibility of NHS England. Where a contract for services by a general practitioner practice is ended, NHS England will look at the provision of services in that area and decide whether to enter into a contract with another provider or to allocate patients to other practices in the area.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England Cheshire and Mersey are unable to release any information while the procurement process is underway.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790106/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:57:00.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790106/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790106/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many bids his Department received in connection with the operation of general practice at the Hightown and Freshfield surgeries.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","113346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790107","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database between 1 May 2017 and 16 November 2017 has identified that 62 items of correspondence were received about the nursing bursaries in general.</p><p> </p><p>We are not able to identify how many of these were specifically about the reintroduction of nursing bursaries.</p><p> </p><p>This figure represents correspondence received by the Department’s Ministerial correspondence unit only.</p><p> </p><p>Between 1 May 2017 and 16 November 2017 my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health has not had any specific meetings with medical professionals or patients on this topic.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790107/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:38:47.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790107/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received form (a) medical professionals and (b) patients on the reintroduction of nursing bursaries.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","113345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790108","Department of Health","false","2017-11-24","<p>Changes to the local NHS services are a matter for the local National Health Service, and form part of the commissioning process. This includes working with local people and with clinicians to ensure that changes are in the best interests of patients. Records of this activity are not held centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790108/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-24T14:14:37.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790108/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Health Services: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many closures have there been of (a) hospital units, (b) GP surgeries, (c) mental health services, (d) walk-in centres, (e) accident and emergency units, (f) maternity units, (g) sexual health clinics, (h) community services, (i) urgent care centres, (j) clinics and (k) paediatric services since 2010; and how many such closures are planned in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","113383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790109","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Skipton Fund was responsible for administering a scheme that made payments to people infected with hepatitis C through treatment with National Health Service blood or blood products and their families. Therefore this fund was open to applications from anyone infected with hepatitis C as a result of receiving anti-d immunoglobin injections. This eligibility continues under the new England Infected Blood Support Scheme.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790109/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:08:45.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790109/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Skipton Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what eligibility criteria the Skipton Fund operates for people infected with HIV or Hepatitis C as a result of receiving anti-d immunoglobin; and what the grounds are for that eligibility criteria.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","113366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790110","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are required to decide on the most appropriate approach to local prioritisation, and may wish to develop a joint plan with others in their Sustainability and Transformation Partnership (STP) in doing so. All CCGs and STPs are required to meet constitutional standards and targets that are set at a national level; including any concerning anti-microbial resistance.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has published a series of ‘Quick Guides’ for STPs, one of which focuses on safety and links into anti-microbial resistance. Each guide sets out what success in 2020 would look like and provides guidance about how areas could approach implementation. These guides can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/stps/resources/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/stps/resources/</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790110/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:11:43.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790110/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to encourage CCGs to prioritise tackling anti-microbial resistance in the work of their sustainability and transformation plans.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","113363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790111","Department of Health","false","2017-11-23","<p>There is a strong association between obesity and the risk of developing Type 2 diabetes. ‘Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action’, launched in 2016, aims to prevent obesity in children and in doing so supports the prevention of Type 2 diabetes in young people.</p><p> </p><p>The plan involves encouraging the food industry to cut the amount of sugar in products, as well as helping children to eat more healthily and stay active. Part of the scheme involves the sugar reduction and wider reformulation programme, which will help reduce the amount of sugar children consume.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Change4Life, Public Health England’s behaviour change social marketing campaign encourages families across England to ‘eat well and move more’.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790111/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:10:42.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790111/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790111/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Diabetes: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to prevent Type 2 diabetes in children.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","113425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790112","Department of Health","false","2017-11-20","<p>A commonly quoted estimate for the number of deaths caused by an antimicrobial resistant (AMR) infection is 5,000 deaths in England each year.</p><p> </p><p>The estimate is also consistent with the Final Report and Recommendations from The Review on Antimicrobial Resistance, chaired by Jim O’Neill. The Review estimated the annual number of deaths caused by AMR infections worldwide to be of the order of 700,000. The report is available at:</p><p><a href="https://amr-review.org/sites/default/files/160525_Final%20paper_with%20cover.pdf" target="_blank">https://amr-review.org/sites/default/files/160525_Final%20paper_with%20cover.pdf</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790112/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:10:13.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790112/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790112/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number of deaths by antimicrobial resistance in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","113428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790113","Department of Health","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Government made £150 million of additional investment available in the 2014 Autumn Statement for children and young people’s eating disorder services (including services for anorexia), over the five years to 2019/20. From April 2017, we established a new eating disorder service waiting time for children and young people – with the ambition that by 2020/21 95% of children will receive treatment within one week for urgent cases and within four weeks for routine cases.</p><p> </p><p>The latest data from NHS England showed that in Q1 2017-18 73.3% of patients started urgent treatment within one week and 78.7% of patients started routine treatment within four weeks.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has now commissioned 70 new or enhanced community services for eating disorders so everyone can get the help they need to manage these conditions. The National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health in partnership with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is developing a pathway for adults with eating disorders, together with detailed implementation guidance for providers, during 2017/18. The pathway will be fully informed by the available evidence and the views of experts.</p><p> </p><p>NICE also published its updated Clinical Guideline: Eating Disorders – recognition and treatment, on managing and treating eating disorders for the over 8s - including adults, children and young people in May 2017.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790113/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T12:32:44.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790113/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/790113/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-15","Anorexia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that people with anorexia have access to timely treatment and early intervention.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","113381"
