"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788982","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-20","<p>There are no plans to make changes to the operation or the administration of the Supreme Court as a result of the UK leaving the EU. We are engaging with both the Supreme Court and the judiciary to ensure that our courts are prepared for any effects of leaving the EU.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788982/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:36:55.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788982/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788982/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-14","Supreme Court","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he has made an assessment of changes to the operation or administration of the Supreme Court as a result of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","112993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788983","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>In line with 2016 Cabinet Office guidance, departments conduct regular tailored reviews of pay review bodies and their status as non-departmental public bodies.</p><p> </p><p>An example of a regular tailored review completed by a department of its pay review body can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/armed-forces-pay-review-body-triennial-review-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/armed-forces-pay-review-body-triennial-review-2014</a></p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788983/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:57:25.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788983/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788983/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the pay review bodies that determine public sector pay.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","112930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788986","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>We recognise the importance of businesses adopting digital technology as this enhances productivity growth. The CBI estimate that increasing business adoption of key technologies and management practices could be worth over £100bn to UK GVA. At Autumn Statement 2016 we announced £13 million funding to support a private sector-led Productivity Leadership Group. The Group will drive engagement to improve business productivity, including through appropriate use of digital technologies.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788986/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T13:43:59.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788986/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788986/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Business: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on productivity of businesses adopting digital technology; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","112803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788987","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-22","<p>The UK government does not have a breakdown of spending per head for islands around Scotland and the rest of the UK. However, the latest figures for 2016-17 public expenditure per capita in Scotland and the rest of the UK were published in the government’s Country and Regional Analysis in November 2017, and can be found at the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630570/60243_PESA_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630570/60243_PESA_Accessible.pdf</a></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788987/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:36:23.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788987/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788987/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the per head spending from the public purse was in 2016-17 on islands around (a) Scotland and (b) the rest of the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Seely","Isle of Wight","Mr Bob Seely","112815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788988","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) held a specific briefing event for managers and the departmental trade unions on 10 November 2015 to share the plans, formally, for its future locations strategy in advance of the announcement on 12 November 2015. This included the detail for all regional centres, specialist sites, transitional sites and a head office presence at Westminster. Prior to this, HMRC held discussions with the unions in confidence about its plans as they developed and in advance of the decisions being made.</p><p> </p><p>The Regional Engagement Group for Glasgow meets on a monthly basis to consider implementation activity for Glasgow, including the moves to Glasgow from East Kilbride and Cumbernauld. There is union representation at these meetings. Topics for discussion are prioritised in accordance with the timeline for office closures in the region. HMRC is retaining East Kilbride as a transitional site until 2025-26 so the detail for this specific move is not yet finalised.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC continues to engage with the unions at both local and national levels throughout the delivery of the Locations Programme.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788988/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T17:08:13.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788988/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788988/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Revenue and Customs: East Kilbride","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 November 2017 to Question 110350, on the proposed transfer of HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) posts from East Kilbride to Glasgow, on what dates meetings between HMRC and departmental trade unions took place.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","112821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788989","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to my previous answer, Hansard Reference 111910. Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) provides an annual estimate of the UK tax gap that includes tax lost through avoidance arrangements that can be challenged under UK law. HMRC does not estimate tax losses outside its jurisdiction.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers have regular discussions with the governments of the Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories on a range of issues, including their commitments to international tax agreements.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788989/answer",,,,,"112870","2017-11-20T15:00:21.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788989/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788989/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Crown Dependencies: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has made an estimate of the scale of tax avoidance in the Crown dependencies.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","112864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788990","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>The flow of direct investment into the UK in the year to Q2 2016 totalled £80.8billion. In the year since the EU referendum, inward foreign direct investment (FDI) flows improved to £158.4billion. This has caused the stock of inward FDI to increase from £1.35trillion in 2016Q2 to £1.49trillion in 2017Q2, an increase of £142bn.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788990/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:25:24.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788990/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788990/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the level of foreign direct investment in the UK was in the 12 months (a) prior to and (b) from July 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","112858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788991","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Valuation Office Agency (VOA) measures performance on an organisation-wide basis, not on an office-by-office basis. Operational work is dealt with across the network of offices, so, for example, a case involving a property in one part of the country could be primarily handled in another part.</p><p> </p><p>Measures of performance, such as those related to timeliness and clearing business rates appeals, are listed in the VOA annual report.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788991/answer",,,,,"112570","2017-11-20T15:06:24.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788991/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788991/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Valuation Office Agency: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the Library any information his Department holds on the performance indicators for individual valuation offices in the UK.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","112859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788992","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to my previous answer, Hansard Reference 111910. Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) provides an annual estimate of the UK tax gap that includes tax lost through avoidance arrangements that can be challenged under UK law. HMRC does not estimate tax losses outside its jurisdiction.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers have regular discussions with the governments of the Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories on a range of issues, including their commitments to international tax agreements.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788992/answer",,,,,"112864","2017-11-20T15:00:21.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788992/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788992/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","British Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 13 November 2017 to Question 111910, whether (a) Government Ministers and (b) HM Revenue and Customs have had discussions with their counterparts in the (i) UK Overseas Territories and (ii) Crown Dependencies to ascertain an estimate of the scale of tax avoidance in those territories.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","112870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788993","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-21","<p>Employees saving into a Save As You Earn scheme may suspend their monthly payments for up to a maximum of six months during the savings period. The Government keeps all aspects of the tax system under review and any changes to eligibility conditions of the scheme would be announced by the Chancellor at a fiscal event.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788993/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T16:06:22.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788993/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788993/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Save as You Earn","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has any plans to review the six-month contribution holiday for Save As You Earn schemes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","112910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788994","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-22","<p>The Autumn Budget 2017 takes steps to put the NHS on a strong and sustainable footing - both now and in the future – with £6.3 billion of additional funding in England. The government will invest £3.5 billion in capital by 2022-23, to ensure patients receive high quality, integrated care and improve efficiency and productivity. The government will also provide an additional £2.8 billion of resource funding to improve NHS performance and ensure that more patients receive the care they need more quickly.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788994/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:53:37.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788994/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788994/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Health Services: Shropshire","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will award increased funding to the NHS in Shropshire in the forthcoming Budget and in particular to the Shropshire and Telford Hospitals NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","112917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788995","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-20","<p>The information requested is not available. The Valuation Office Agency does not monitor numbers of individual cases processed at each of its locations.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788995/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T14:40:04.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788995/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788995/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-14","Valuation Office Agency: Rhyl","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 13 November 2017 to Question 111680, how many individual cases the Rhyl valuation office has processed in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","112988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788996","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-20","<p>There are various different types of mediated access schemes being operated across the country, including Help to Rent projects and Guarantee deposit schemes. We are considering how best to take forward a mediated access in the context of our overall homelessness prevention approach.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788996/answer",,,,,"112997 ; 112998 ; 112999","2017-11-20T15:29:38.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788996/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788996/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-14","Private Rented Housing: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110466, on private rented housing: homelessness, what the timetable is for the conclusion and publication of his consideration of the effectiveness of existing projects.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","112996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788997","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-20","<p>There are various different types of mediated access schemes being operated across the country, including Help to Rent projects and Guarantee deposit schemes. We are considering how best to take forward a mediated access in the context of our overall homelessness prevention approach.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788997/answer",,,,,"112996 ; 112998 ; 112999","2017-11-20T15:29:38.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788997/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788997/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-14","Private Rented Housing: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110466, on private rented housing: homelessness, which projects are included in his consideration of the effectiveness of existing projects.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","112997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788998","Department for Education","false","2017-11-22","<p>Information on the turnover of children’s social workers in local authorities in England has been collected on a comparable basis as of 30 September each year since 2013. The most recent data was published by the department on 16 February 2017 and is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-childrens-social-care-workforce" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-childrens-social-care-workforce</a>.</p><p>The requested data is shown below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>As at 30 September</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Redcar and Cleveland</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>North East</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>19%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>9%</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note: turnover rates have been calculated using the number of leavers during the year ending 30 September as a percentage of the number of children’s social workers at 30 September.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788998/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T13:53:32.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788998/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788998/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Social Workers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the employee turnover rate for social workers in (a) Redcar and Cleveland Borough Council, (b) the North East and (c) England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","113035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788999","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-22","<p>Since the introduction of the Sustainable Communities Act 2007 and its extension to include town and parish councils in October 2014, 33 proposals have been received. A list of these authorities will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788999/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:39:27.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788999/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/788999/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-14","Sustainable Communities Act 2007","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities, parish and town councils have submitted proposals to his Department under the Sustainable Communities Act 2007 since its inception.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","112959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789000","Department for Education","false","2017-11-22","<p>The government is clear that the needs of the child are paramount when making decisions about the right care placement. Local councils have a statutory duty to consider the right placement for each child and take into account a number of factors, one of which is placement area. Sometimes circumstances make it the right decision for a local council to identify a placement outside of the child’s local area, for example when a child is at risk from child sexual exploitation, trafficking or gang violence or when they need very specialist care.</p><p> </p><p>Out of area placements require approval from the Director of Children’s Services, and Ofsted will challenge local councils where they believe poor out of area placement are being made. The government is funding Innovation Programme pilots for residential care in areas where demand for residential places outstrips supply. We are also setting up a Residential Care Leadership Board, which will bring together representatives from local councils and providers to explore how to improve commissioning of children’s residential placements. As part of this work we expect the Board to assess data on the use of out of area placements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789000/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T13:52:01.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789000/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789000/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the number of looked-after children being placed 20 miles or more outside the boundary of their local authority.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","113036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789001","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-23","<p>Annual expenditure data by each local authority for all services, including children’s services, are published on the Department’s website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789001/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T15:52:39.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789001/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789001/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-14","Social Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of local authorities' budgets have been spent on children's services by (a) Redcar and Cleveland Borough Council, (b) local authorities in the North East and (c) local authorities in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","113037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789002","Department for Education","false","2017-11-22","<p>Local councils as employers are responsible for the provision of appropriate pastoral support. The Standards for Employers of Social Workers, published by the Local Government Association, provide an important means of ensuring that employers are providing the right support to social workers in the difficult work they do.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789002/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T13:50:42.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789002/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789002/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Social Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that local authorities provide adequate pastoral support for social workers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","113038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789003","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-22","<p>There are no specific powers relating to bike-share schemes, however shared bicycles are subject to the same legal requirements and byelaws as other bicycles, and local authorities have powers to act if they are causing an obstruction or nuisance. The Department is discussing with various stakeholders the possible need for an agreed consistent national standard for bike share schemes to help ensure that they are introduced and managed appropriately.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789003/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T12:04:17.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789003/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789003/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-14","Bicycles: Hire Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers local authorities in England have to regulate bike share schemes within their boundaries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","112924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789004","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>(a) The Government has received five direct requests to departments for financial support as a result of the appalling Manchester terrorist attack.</p><p>(b) The Government has to date provided financial assistance on a wide range of areas to support the ongoing recovery operation in Manchester. This includes £185,000 for an Education Psychologist Programme to help young people impacted by the attack; £337,000 in 2017/18 for support to victims of terrorist attacks, including £79,000 specifically to support services in Manchester and a £276,000 donation to the We Love Manchester Emergency Fund. Government is in conversation with VisitBritain to explore ways in which we continue to support and promote Manchester and the surrounding region. Furthermore, charitable payments from the We Love Manchester Emergency Fund have been disregarded in the calculation of income-related benefits since June 2017. The Prime Minister has committed to responding in full to the outstanding requests for additional funding from the Greater Manchester Mayor before 26th November 2017.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789004/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-23T14:31:57.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789004/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789004/answer","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789004/answer/previousversion/23683","Biography information for Damian Green","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-14","Terrorism: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many requests for financial support the Government has (a) received and (b) granted as a result of the 2017 Manchester terrorist attack.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","112932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789005","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-20","<p>There are various different types of mediated access schemes being operated across the country, including Help to Rent projects and Guarantee deposit schemes. We are considering how best to take forward a mediated access in the context of our overall homelessness prevention approach.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789005/answer",,,,,"112996 ; 112997 ; 112999","2017-11-20T15:29:38.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789005/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789005/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-14","Private Rented Housing: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110466, on private rented housing: homelessness, in what way he is considering the effectiveness of existing projects operating across the country.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","112998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789006","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-20","<p>There are various different types of mediated access schemes being operated across the country, including Help to Rent projects and Guarantee deposit schemes. We are considering how best to take forward a mediated access in the context of our overall homelessness prevention approach.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789006/answer",,,,,"112996 ; 112997 ; 112998","2017-11-20T15:29:38.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789006/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789006/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-14","Private Rented Housing: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2017 to Question 110466, on private rented housing: homelessness, what projects were previously notified of the measures he is using in considering the effectiveness of existing projects operating across the country.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","112999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789007","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that victims of terrorist attacks receive the help and support they need. The Ministry of Justice has allocated £96m to funding for services supporting victims of crime in 2017/18, with the majority of funding allocated to Police and Crime Commissioners and some services commissioned nationally. This includes funding for the national Homicide Service which supports families bereaved by murder including terrorism; and for the Peace Foundation which supports victims and families affected by terrorism.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice has provided an additional £337,000 in 2017/18 to help ensure services provide the best possible support to victims of terrorist attacks, including £79,000 specifically to support services in Manchester.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also established a cross-departmental Victims of Terrorism Unit, to help coordinate support for victims of terrorist attacks including Manchester, across the statutory and voluntary sector and at national and local level. This has included work with local schools to help ensure that children and teachers have support in coping with the attacks, ensuring that payments from charitable fundraising does not affect victims’ income related benefits, and work with local authorities to ensure that best practice is shared and adopted.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789007/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T15:53:56.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789007/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789007/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-14","Terrorism: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much financial support has been provided to services offering support for families and victims of the Manchester terrorist attack of 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","112939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789009","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-22","<p>The Department does not hold information on current average broadband speed in either rural or urban areas. The 2016 Ofcom Connected Nations report showed that across the UK the average download speed is 37Mit/s.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789009/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T15:27:08.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789009/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789009/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-14","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of average broadband speeds in (a) rural and (b) urban areas.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","112823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789010","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-22","<p>The Department does not hold information on current average broadband speed by constituency. This information can be located on Thinkbroadband (http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/england)</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789010/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T15:28:29.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789010/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789010/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-14","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what statistics her Department holds on average broadband speeds on a constituency basis.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","112903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789011","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-22","<p>Our aim is to secure a relationship that provides for practical operational cooperation; facilitates data driven law enforcement; and allows multilateral cooperation through EU agencies.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789011/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T15:19:56.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789011/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789011/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-14","European Network and Information Security Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government plans to seek third country participation with the European Union Agency for Network and Information Security under Article 30 of the Regulations (EU) No. 526/2013 after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","113005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789012","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-22","<p>The EU Regulation (1211/2009) establishing the Body of European Regulators for Electronic Communications (BEREC) is currently subject to review as part of the recast of the EU Regulatory Framework for Communications. We are seeking a deep and special future partnership with the European Union. The UK’s relationship with the European Union’s agencies and bodies upon exit will be evaluated on this basis. The Government is carefully considering a range of options and no decisions have yet been made on the UK’s future relationship with the EU’s agencies and bodies, including BEREC.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789012/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T15:24:28.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789012/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789012/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-14","Body of European Regulators for Electronic Communications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the UK plans to seek observer status at the Body of European Regulators for Electronic Communications after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","112897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789013","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Government is hugely supportive of the NFL in London, and welcome the investment and economic benefits. The Government’s sport strategy, Sporting Future, made a commitment to support new sports in the UK, including through greater links with the National Football League, with the aspiration that a new franchise might one day be based here.</p><p> </p><p>This year marked ten years of London hosting the NFL International Series. Sell outs and the extra game this year show the appetite for NFL in the UK is growing. The NFL's executive vice president of international, Mark Waller, recently stated the NFL's ambition remains to bring a franchise to London by 2022.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789013/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T10:05:48.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789013/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789013/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-14","National Football League","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on establishing a National Football League franchise in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","112994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789014","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The number of live quarry killed during trail or drag hunting on Ministry of Defence land in the past five years is shown below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of Live Kills recorded</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789014/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:56:24.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789014/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789014/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Ministry of Defence: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many live quarry have been killed during a trial hunt on Ministry of Defence land in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Duffield","Canterbury","Rosie Duffield","113019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789015","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The information requested is not held in the format requested.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789015/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:54:48.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789015/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789015/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Ministry of Defence: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many licences for trail hunts have been issued for Ministry of Defence land in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Duffield","Canterbury","Rosie Duffield","113024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789016","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>The safety of the public, our submarine crews, the defence workforce and the protection of the environment remain the Department's priority. Overall, the Defence Nuclear Programme achieves the required standards of nuclear and radiological safety. Nuclear safety has not been compromised.</p><p>The Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator Annual Assurance Reports for the periods 2015-16 and 2016-17 will not be published as it has been assessed to do so would impact national security. This does not prevent the effective management and independent assessment of the Defence Nuclear Programme, nor prevent its duty holders being held to account, but we cannot accept any compromise of our capabilities in the current security climate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789016/answer",,,,,"113220 ; 113221","2017-11-21T14:52:33.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789016/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789016/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the safety of the Trident nuclear weapons system; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","112915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789017","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>Planned nuclear infrastructure projects at Faslane and Coulport are funded separately from the budget for the Dreadnought programme.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789017/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T14:45:00.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789017/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789017/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Nuclear Weapons: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether expenditure for planned nuclear infrastructure projects at Faslane and Coulport will come out of the existing budget for Trident.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","112914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789018","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>Combat Stress’ contract with NHS England for the provision of places on a six week residential intensive programme for veterans living in England finishes on 31 March 2018. It is for Combat Stress to decide how they operate in the future. However, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) understands that Combat Stress has no plans to close Audley Court.</p><p> </p><p>We encourage Service personnel and veterans wishing to seek help with mental health problems to visit: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/mental-health-support-for-the-uk-armed-forces" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/mental-health-support-for-the-uk-armed-forces</a>. Veterans can also call the 24-hour veterans’ mental health helpline, provided by Combat Stress, on 0800 138 1619. Information and advice on services is available through the MOD’s Veterans UK or the Veterans Gateway.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789018/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T14:49:23.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789018/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789018/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Veterans: Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will hold discussions with the Board of Combat Stress on its plans to end residential care for veterans at Audley Court, Newport, Shropshire.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","112916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789019","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 13 November 2017 to Question 111415 to the hon. Member for Inverclyde (Ronnie Cowan).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789019/answer","Hansard Extract  Monday 13 November 2017, HOC 111415.docx","Hansard Extract  Monday 13 November 2017, HOC 111415.docx","111415 - WQnA extract on Trident Submarines","111415 - WQnA extract on Trident Submarines",,"2017-11-21T14:43:39.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789019/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789019/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether additional funds will be allocated to the Trident replacement programme in the 2017-18 financial year which have not already been budgeted for.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","112918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789020","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-22","<p>The costs of the nuclear infrastructure projects are:</p><p>Faslane Nuclear Infrastructure Continuous Availability Project - £507 million</p><p>Coulport Infrastructure Continuous Availability Project - £289 million</p><p>Faslane Nuclear Support Hub Project - £76 million</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789020/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:05:09.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789020/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789020/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Nuclear Weapons: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will list the costs of the Government's planned nuclear infrastructure projects at Faslane and Coulport.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","112912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789021","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-21","<p>Three current projects to improve infrastructure are currently taking place: Faslane Nuclear Infrastructure Continuous Availability Project, Coulport Infrastructure Continuous Availability Project and the Nuclear Support Hub Project.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789021/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T14:44:21.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789021/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789021/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Nuclear Weapons: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what specific projects and programmes are scheduled to take place to expand nuclear infrastructure at Faslane and Coulport.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","112913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789022","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Royal Navy provides six apprenticeships in:</p><p>Business Administration and Law;</p><p>Engineering and Manufacturing Technologies;</p><p>Health, Public Service and Care;</p><p>Information and Communication Technology;</p><p>Leisure, Travel and Tourism;</p><p>Retail and Commercial Enterprise.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789022/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:09:36.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789022/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789022/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Navy: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many apprenticeships the Royal Navy provides; and in which sectors.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","112877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789023","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Army is Britain's biggest provider of apprenticeships, offering not just a job, but a career with ongoing training. It currently runs 43 apprenticeship programmes, across seven sectors:</p><p>Engineering and Manufacturing Technologies;</p><p>Retail and Commercial Enterprise;</p><p>Health, Public Services and Care;</p><p>Information and Communication Technology;</p><p>Business, Administration and Law;</p><p>Construction, Planning and the Built Environment;</p><p>Agriculture, Horticulture and Animal Care.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789023/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T16:10:13.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789023/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789023/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Army: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many apprenticeships the British Army provides and in which sectors.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","112886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789024","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Royal Air Force currently has approximately 2800 individuals undertaking apprenticeships on 16 different programmes in:</p><p>Engineering Manufacture (Operator and Semi-Skilled);</p><p>Catering And Professional Chefs;</p><p>Hospitality;</p><p>Warehousing and Storage;</p><p>HM Forces;</p><p>Providing Security Services;</p><p>Aviation Operations OnThe Ground;</p><p>Driving Goods Vehicles;</p><p>Engineering Manufacture (Craft and Technician);</p><p>Information Technology, Software, Web and Telecoms Professionals;</p><p>Aviation Operations On The Ground;</p><p>Information Technology Application Specialist;</p><p>Photo Imaging;</p><p>Business Administration;</p><p>Health (Clinical Healthcare Support);</p><p>Intelligence Operations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789024/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:03:17.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789024/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789024/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-14","Air Force: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many apprenticeships the Royal Air Force provides and in which sectors.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","112887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789025","Department for Education","false","2017-11-22","<p>Knowledge about politics is an important part of a broad and balanced education that prepares young people for adult life. Citizenship education is in the statutory national curriculum at key stages 3 and 4. The programmes of study are designed to prepare pupils to play a full and active part in society, and are organised around core knowledge about democracy, government, and how laws are made and upheld. Citizenship education also equips pupils with the knowledge to explore political and social issues, to weigh evidence, debate and make reasoned arguments. Schools can also teach politics as part of their school curriculum if they choose to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789025/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:42:35.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789025/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789025/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Politics: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to add political education to the national curriculum.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","112904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789026","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Data Exchange Project began with a small team in 2013 exploring options to modernise the flow of data across the sector in response to an Independent Analytical Review. A project, focusing on how best to deliver the current intended scope and benefits, began in January 2016. Consultation since then has included regular testing and research with schools, proportionate to the stage of the project.</p><p>The project has undertaken an initial privacy impact screening assessment. This is reviewed as work progresses to ensure all privacy risks are regularly assessed. Data Exchange has recently passed its end Alpha phase Government Digital Service (GDS) assessment, demonstrating the approach taken so far has clearly understood the risks and benefits associated with change. Passing that GDS assessment requires demonstration of regular work alongside users in schools (and elsewhere), to design an approach that will benefit schools and others without adding unnecessary complexity, risk or burden.</p><p>A copy of the latest initial impact screening assessment has been placed in the House library.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789026/answer",,,,,"112861","2017-11-20T16:30:57.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789026/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789026/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Department for Education: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the Data Exchange project began; and what progress has been made in achieving the aims of that project.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","112860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789027","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Data Exchange Project began with a small team in 2013 exploring options to modernise the flow of data across the sector in response to an Independent Analytical Review. A project, focusing on how best to deliver the current intended scope and benefits, began in January 2016. Consultation since then has included regular testing and research with schools, proportionate to the stage of the project.</p><p>The project has undertaken an initial privacy impact screening assessment. This is reviewed as work progresses to ensure all privacy risks are regularly assessed. Data Exchange has recently passed its end Alpha phase Government Digital Service (GDS) assessment, demonstrating the approach taken so far has clearly understood the risks and benefits associated with change. Passing that GDS assessment requires demonstration of regular work alongside users in schools (and elsewhere), to design an approach that will benefit schools and others without adding unnecessary complexity, risk or burden.</p><p>A copy of the latest initial impact screening assessment has been placed in the House library.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789027/answer",,,,,"112860","2017-11-20T16:30:57.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789027/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789027/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Department for Education: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish impact and risk assessments undertaken on schools for the Data Exchange project.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","112861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789028","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>Officials engage with their counterparts in the devolved administrations to share best practice on topics of mutual interest and concern. Improving the education attainment of young people from disadvantaged backgrounds is a regular topic at the twice-yearly four nations meetings facilitated by the British Council – the last meeting took place 7-8 November. It was also a theme of the International Summit on the Teaching Profession (ISTP). The published report from ISTP - <a href="http://asiasociety.org/global-cities-education-network/empowering-and-enabling-teachers-improve-equity-and-outcomes-all" target="_blank">http://asiasociety.org/global-cities-education-network/empowering-and-enabling-teachers-improve-equity-and-outcomes-all</a> - illustrates how England and Scotland shared recent initiatives aimed at breaking the link between social deprivation and educational and adult success.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789028/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:17:06.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789028/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789028/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to share best practice with and from the devolved Parliament and Assemblies on delivering improvements in educational attainment among young people from disadvantaged backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","112854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789029","Department for Education","false","2017-11-22","<p>The department has made no assessment of the number of children who are at risk of experiencing hunger during school Christmas holidays in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently giving full consideration to the School Holidays (Meals and Activities) Bill, which considers this issue, and will be responding in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789029/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:40:22.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789029/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789029/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of children who are at risk of experiencing hunger during the school Christmas holidays in 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","112829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789030","Department for Education","false","2017-11-22","<p>The department recognises the importance of ensuring that teachers are well equipped to support children and young people with special educational needs or a disability, including those with autism. We are unable to comment on continuing funding for the Autism Education Trust, as decisions about Special Educational Needs and Disabilities contracts for next financial year are still under consideration.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789030/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-22T16:39:48.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789030/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789030/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will continue to fund the Autism Education Trust to help ensure that teachers in England can access training in autism as part of their continuous professional development.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","112817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789031","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>The number of pupils, at the end of KS4[1], with at least two entries[2] into arts subjects at GCSE level (including equivalents)[3] in Coventry[4] is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year<strong>[5]</strong></strong></p></td><td><p>Pupils entering at least two arts subjects at GCSE</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>216</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>319</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>372</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>236</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>288</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] Pupils are identified as being at the end of key stage 4 if they were on roll at the school and in year 11 at the time of the January school census for that year. Age is calculated as at 31 August for that year, and the majority of pupils at the end of key stage 4 were age 15 at the start of the academic year. Some pupils may complete this key stage in an earlier or later year group.</p><p>[2] In line with secondary performance measures and early entry policy, discounting has been applied. More information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/key-stage-4-qualifications-discount-codes-and-point-scores" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/key-stage-4-qualifications-discount-codes-and-point-scores</a>.</p><p>[3] Includes: Applied Art &amp; Design, Art &amp; Design, Drama, Performing Arts, Media/Film/TV Studies, Music and Dance. Does not include History of Art and Creative Writing. Includes GCSE full courses, level 2 equivalents, GCSE double awards and AS levels.</p><p>[4] All pupils at the end of key stage 4 who attend a school in the local authority of Coventry.</p><p>[5] 2016 data is final and may differ from previously published figures. 2017 data is provisional.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789031/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-20T17:09:43.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789031/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789031/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-14","Arts: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many students have studied at least two arts subjects at GCSE level in Coventry in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","112806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/789032","Department for Education","false","2017-11-20","<p>The number of entries<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/112807_PQ%20Team%20QA%201611.docx#_ftn1" target="_blank">[1]</a> into arts subjects at GCSE level (including equivalents)<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/112807_PQ%20Team%20QA%201611.docx#_ftn2" target="_blank">[2]</a>, by pupils at the end of key stage 4<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/112807_PQ%20Team%20QA%201611.docx#_ftn3" target="_blank">[3]</a> in Coventry<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/112807_PQ%20Team%20QA%201611.docx#_ftn4" target="_blank">[4]</a> is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/112807_PQ%20Team%20QA%201611.docx#_ftn5" target="_blank"><strong>[5]</strong></a></strong></p></td><td><p>Number of entries into arts subjects GCSE</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1,409</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>1,849</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2,104</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>1,747</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>1,828</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/112807_PQ%20Team%20QA%201611.docx#_ftnref1" target="_blank">[1]</a> In line with secondary performance measures and early entry policy, discounting has been applied. More information can be found at: <a href